// Pipeline Stage Overviews — detailed "what actually happens" narratives
// Keyed by stage ID (s01–s16)
// Each entry: { what, before, after, steps[], duration, team, deliverables[] }

export const STAGE_OVERVIEWS = {

  s01: {
    what: `Gene Construction is the molecular blueprint phase — the very first CMC act in building a biologic drug. Starting with a protein target identified by drug discovery (a receptor-blocking antibody, a receptor-blocking enzyme, etc.), the CMC team must convert the desired amino acid sequence into a stable, high-performance DNA construct capable of driving industrial-scale protein expression in a Chinese Hamster Ovary (CHO) cell factory.\n\nThe key challenge is that the genetic code is redundant — most amino acids can be encoded by 2–6 different codons, and CHO cells have strong codon preferences. A gene written in human or natural codon frequencies will be read slowly and inefficiently by CHO ribosomes. Through computational codon optimization, every codon in the sequence is reassessed and replaced with the CHO-preferred variant, unlocking 3–10× titer improvements before a single experiment is run.\n\nBeyond the coding sequence itself, the expression vector — the DNA vehicle that carries the gene — must be carefully engineered. A promoter must drive transcription; a selection cassette must allow identification of high-producing cells; a signal peptide must direct the protein through the secretory pathway. Every genetic element filed in the first IND becomes a permanent record. This stage ends when a sequence-confirmed, fully annotated expression construct is ready to be transfected into CHO cells.`,
    before: `Drug discovery delivers: (1) the target protein's amino acid sequence (often the antibody variable regions from hybridoma or phage display), (2) early proof-of-concept binding and efficacy data, and (3) a molecule nomination decision. There is no upstream CMC stage — this is where CMC begins.`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 02 (Transfection): A fully verified, BLA-ready expression vector containing the codon-optimized heavy and light chain coding sequences, selection marker, and all regulatory elements. This vector is the permanent genetic raw material for every batch ever manufactured.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Amino Acid Sequence Acquisition", detail: "The drug discovery team hands over the full amino acid sequence (for a mAb: VH+VL CDRs + framework + constant regions). The CMC team confirms complete heavy chain + light chain sequences, signal peptide strategy, and any Fc engineering modifications (LALA, YTE, afucosylation mutations, etc.)." },
      { num: 2, title: "Developability Assessment", detail: "Before spending months on gene synthesis, in silico tools screen the sequence for CMC liabilities: CDR deamidation hotspots (Asn-Gly, Asn-Ser motifs), oxidation-prone residues (Met/Trp in CDRs), isomerization-prone sequences (Asp-Pro), aggregation-prone regions (APRs), and viscosity risk. Physical screens (DLS, CSI-ELISA, HIC retention) may be run on transiently expressed material. Sequences with high-risk liabilities may be engineered to remove them before proceeding." },
      { num: 3, title: "Codon Optimization", detail: "Computational software (GeneArt, Twist, proprietary algorithms) replaces every codon in the sequence with the CHO-preferred equivalent while maintaining the protein sequence exactly. The resulting optimized DNA sequence typically has a Codon Adaptation Index (CAI) > 0.8 vs. the original 0.6–0.7. This is the single highest-ROI productivity intervention in the entire program." },
      { num: 4, title: "Expression Vector Design", detail: "The optimized coding sequence is embedded into the expression vector backbone. Decisions made here include: promoter selection (CMV vs. EF1α vs. CAG — strength vs. long-term stability tradeoff), selection marker (GS-knockout CHO with MSX for fast ~4-week selection, or DHFR-deficient CHO-DG44 with MTX amplification for 8+ weeks but higher copy), Kozak sequence for translation initiation, poly-A signal, internal ribosome entry site (IRES) or 2A peptide if dual-gene expression is used. For a mAb, heavy and light chains typically occupy separate transcription units on one vector or two co-transfected vectors." },
      { num: 5, title: "Signal Peptide Selection", detail: "The signal peptide (typically 15–30 amino acids at the N-terminus) directs the protein into the endoplasmic reticulum for secretion. Native IgG signal peptides, optimized synthetic sequences, or murine Ig leader sequences are evaluated. The choice affects mRNA stability, translocation efficiency, and — critically — whether signal peptide cleavage is complete and accurate. Incomplete cleavage creates N-terminal extension heterogeneity that becomes a CQA." },
      { num: 6, title: "Gene Synthesis & Sequence Verification", detail: "The finalized, codon-optimized gene sequences are ordered from a gene synthesis vendor (Twist Bioscience, GeneArt/Thermo, IDT). Synthesized fragments are received and cloned into the expression vector backbone using restriction enzyme or Gibson Assembly cloning. The complete construct is Sanger-sequenced (or NGS-sequenced for NGS-quality confirmation) to confirm 100% sequence fidelity. Any sequence errors identified here are corrected before transfection. This is the final identity confirmation of the genetic material going into cells." },
      { num: 7, title: "QTPP Initiation & CQA Identification (Start)", detail: "In parallel with gene work, the CMC team drafts the Quality Target Product Profile (QTPP) — the desired characteristics of the final drug product (dosage form, route, strength, CQA targets, shelf life). The QTPP drives all downstream CMC decisions. An initial CQA risk assessment identifies which quality attributes have safety/efficacy relevance and require control (glycosylation, aggregation, potency, endotoxin, etc.)." },
    ],
    duration: "4–8 weeks for gene synthesis and vector construction; developability assessment may add 4–8 weeks",
    team: "Molecular Biology, Protein Engineering, Early CMC/Pharmaceutical Sciences, Drug Discovery (hand-off)",
    deliverables: [
      "Codon-optimized, sequence-confirmed expression vector",
      "Developability assessment report with sequence liability analysis",
      "Initial QTPP document",
      "Signal peptide cleavage design rationale",
      "Gene synthesis and sequence verification records",
    ],
  },

  s02: {
    what: `Transfection and Integration is the step where the expression vector — the genetic blueprint built in Stage 01 — is physically delivered into CHO cells and stably integrated into their genome. This is the conversion from 'DNA on paper' to 'living cell factory'.\n\nTransfection introduces foreign DNA into cells. Transient transfection (using HEK293E or ExpiCHO cells) can produce milligrams of material in 7–10 days without stable integration, enabling early feasibility studies. However, transient material cannot serve as clinical supply without an extensive bridging comparability package. Stable transfection integrates the vector permanently into the CHO genome, ensuring every daughter cell inherits and expresses the gene — the foundation of commercial manufacturing.\n\nThe most critical quality dimension of this stage is clonality assurance. FDA and EMA require documented proof that each candidate clone originated from a single parent cell, because only a clonal cell line guarantees genetic uniformity. Since 2021, FDA has required day-zero imaging evidence for every single-cell deposition event. Missing these images is an irreversible gap that cannot be reconstructed post-hoc and has triggered Complete Response Letters at BLA review.`,
    before: `Receives from Stage 01: Sequence-confirmed expression vector (plasmid DNA, typically prepared at clinical-grade or development-grade depending on regulatory intent), and a confirmed CHO host cell line (either GS-knockout CHO or DHFR-deficient CHO-DG44 depending on selection system chosen).`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 03 (CLD): Stable transfected cell pools — diverse populations of cells all expressing the gene of interest. Some clones will be high producers; most will not. Stage 03 identifies and isolates the best single-cell clone from this population.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Host Cell Line Preparation & Expansion", detail: "The chosen CHO host cell line (GS-knockout CHO-K1, CHO-S, or DHFR-deficient CHO-DG44) is expanded from the lab cell bank into suspension culture in chemically defined media (CDM) under controlled conditions. Cell health, viability (>95%), doubling time, and media adaptation are confirmed before transfection. This typically takes 1–2 weeks." },
      { num: 2, title: "Plasmid DNA Preparation", detail: "The expression vector is prepared by large-scale bacterial culture (E. coli) followed by maxi-prep purification (endotoxin-free). DNA is linearized (for stable integration — linearization improves integration frequency) or used supercoiled (for some transient applications). DNA quantity and quality are confirmed by spectrophotometry (A260/280 ratio) and agarose gel electrophoresis." },
      { num: 3, title: "Electroporation / Transfection", detail: "Stable transfection most commonly uses electroporation: a high-voltage electrical pulse temporarily permeabilizes the cell membrane, allowing DNA to enter. Optimized pulse parameters (voltage, duration, cell density) are established for the specific CHO host line. Lipofection (cationic lipid-mediated delivery) and nucleofection (nuclear-targeted electroporation) are alternative methods used less commonly for stable CHO lines. Transfection efficiency is monitored by transient expression testing 24–48 h post-transfection." },
      { num: 4, title: "Drug Selection — Creating Stable Pools", detail: "Two to three days post-transfection, selection pressure is applied: methionine sulfoximine (MSX) for GS-knockout CHO lines, or methotrexate (MTX) for DHFR-deficient CHO-DG44 lines. Cells without stable vector integration lack the selection marker (glutamine synthetase or DHFR) and die within 2–4 weeks. Surviving cells have stably integrated the expression construct. The resulting 'stable pool' — a heterogeneous population of expressing clones — is expanded and screened." },
      { num: 5, title: "Stable Pool Screening & Titer Assessment", detail: "Stable pools are grown in fed-batch conditions (typically in shake flasks or 24-well plates) and end-point titers measured by Protein A HPLC or ELISA. High-expressing pools are selected as the starting material for single-cell cloning. Multiple pools may be generated from different transfection experiments or conditions to maximize the diversity of the candidate clone funnel." },
      { num: 6, title: "Single-Cell Deposition — Clonality Assurance", detail: "FDA's 2021 guidance and ICH Q5D require two rounds of single-cell subcloning. Accepted methods: (1) limiting dilution (mean cell density ≤0.5 cells/well, Poisson statistics giving >86% probability of single-cell origin), (2) FACS single-cell deposition (fluorescence-activated sorting of individual cells), or (3) automated single-cell imaging systems (ClonePix2, Solentim VIPS). Day 0 or Day 1 images of each single-cell deposit must be captured and archived permanently — this imaging record is the foundation of clonality documentation. Typically 500–1,000 single-cell depositions per pool." },
      { num: 7, title: "Clone Recovery, Expansion & Initial Screening", detail: "Over 2–4 weeks, surviving clones expand into visible colonies. Recovery rates from single-cell deposition are typically 30–70% (not every single cell survives cloning). Day 1–14 images are captured at defined intervals to document colony outgrowth. Growing clones are transferred to 24-well plates, then 6-well plates. An initial high-throughput titer screen (Protein A magnetic beads or ELISA) identifies the top 10–20% of clones by productivity. This funnel feeds into the Cell Line Development stage." },
    ],
    duration: "8–14 weeks from transfection to stable, screened clone candidates ready for CLD",
    team: "Cell Line Development (CLD) Scientists, Molecular Biology, Early CMC",
    deliverables: [
      "Stable transfected cell pools with documented selection conditions",
      "Day-0 and Day-1 single-cell deposition images (archived, regulatory-ready)",
      "Initial titer screen data for 96-well plate clone candidates",
      "Transfection parameters and selection conditions record",
      "Pool characterization data (viability, growth, productivity)",
    ],
  },

  s03: {
    what: `Cell Line Development (CLD) is the most consequential stage in the entire biologic CMC program. From hundreds of genetically diverse candidate clones, the CLD team must identify the single best clone — the one that will manufacture every commercial batch for the drug's entire lifecycle, potentially 15–25 years.\n\nA clone is not just selected for productivity. The highest-titer clone may produce too many aggregates, have the wrong glycan profile, or accumulate a specific impurity at levels difficult to clear downstream. A metabolically inefficient clone may perform well at 10L but fail at 10,000L. The selection funnel therefore simultaneously evaluates productivity (specific productivity qP), growth characteristics, product quality attributes (glycosylation, aggregation, charge variants, HCP profile), and genetic stability indicators.\n\nThe selection funnel is typically: ~500 96-well plate clones → 48-well plates → 12 ambr15 microscale bioreactor runs → 4 shake flask fed-batch runs → 2 benchtop bioreactor runs → 1 lead clone (+ 2–3 backups). Each stage of the funnel combines more manufacturing-representative conditions with deeper quality profiling. The final selection is a scientific and strategic decision with multi-hundred-million-dollar consequences.`,
    before: `Receives from Stage 02: Stable transfected cell pools with initial titer screening data, day-0 single-cell deposition images, and a ranked list of candidate clones by preliminary productivity from 96-well plate screens.`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 04 (Cell Banking): A lead production clone (and 2–3 backup clones) with documented selection rationale, productivity data, preliminary CQA profiling, initial genetic stability indicators, and a unique STR fingerprint. These clones go directly into cell banking.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "96-Well Deep Well Plate Primary Screen", detail: "Hundreds of single-cell clones from Stage 02 are expanded into 96-well deep well plates in fed-batch-like batch culture (no feeding, 7–10 day culture). End-point titer is measured by automated Protein A or Octet biolayer interferometry. Viability and growth curves are plotted. The top 10–20% by titer (typically ~50–100 clones) advance to the next funnel stage. Speed and throughput are paramount here — this is purely a titer screen." },
      { num: 2, title: "24-Well / Shake Flask Fed-Batch Screen", detail: "The top clones are grown in 24-well plates or small shake flasks under fed-batch conditions with the same base media and feed strategy planned for development. Fed-batch mimics the real process better than batch mode. Titer (by Protein A HPLC), viability profiles, and initial product quality (aggregation by SEC-HPLC on Protein A-purified micro-prep material) are assessed. Typically 50–100 → 20–30 clones advance." },
      { num: 3, title: "ambr15 / ambr250 Microscale Bioreactor Screen", detail: "The automated micro bioreactor systems (ambr15 or ambr250 from Sartorius) provide 12–24 fully instrumented bioreactor vessels at 15–250 mL scale with pH, DO, temperature, and agitation control. This is the most discriminating productivity screen — the ambr closely mimics the commercial-scale bioreactor environment. Clones are run in 10–14 day fed-batch campaigns. Data collected: titer, growth kinetics, metabolic profile (glucose, lactate, glutamine, ammonia), and product quality (SEC-HPLC aggregation, icIEF charge variants, glycan profiling by UHPLC). Typically 20–30 → 8–12 clones advance." },
      { num: 4, title: "CQA Profiling on Purified Material", detail: "For the top 8–12 clones, small-scale Protein A purification (spin columns or small prepacked columns) yields 1–5 mg of purified material per clone. This material is characterized for: N-glycan profile (G0F/G1F/G2F/Man5/afucosylated species) by UHPLC or CE-based glycan analysis; aggregation by SEC-HPLC; charge variants by icIEF; purity by CE-SDS (non-reducing and reducing); initial HCP profile by ELISA. Clones with high aggregation propensity, unfavorable glycan profiles, or unusual charge variant patterns are deprioritized even if their titer is competitive." },
      { num: 5, title: "Metabolic & HCP Profile Analysis", detail: "Metabolic efficiency is assessed by calculating the lactate/glucose ratio over time and identifying whether clones exhibit the desirable 'lactate switch' (reversal from lactate production to consumption mid-culture — a sign of efficient metabolism). Ammonia accumulation is measured (high ammonia disrupts Golgi pH and glycosylation). For programs where PLBL2 or other high-risk HCPs are a concern, LC-MS-based HCP profiling during CLD can identify clones with unfavorable HCP repertoires before they advance." },
      { num: 6, title: "Bench/2L Bioreactor Confirmation Runs", detail: "The final 3–5 clone candidates are grown in 2L benchtop bioreactors using the preliminary upstream process conditions. This provides the most commercially representative data in CLD: full instrumentation, gas sparging, pH/DO control, and representative sampling. The runs generate sufficient material (50–200 mg purified) for an extended CQA characterization panel including potency assay, higher-order structure (HOS) assessment by CD or DSF, and initial forced degradation. Process comparability between clones is assessed — smaller batch-to-batch differences are preferred." },
      { num: 7, title: "Lead Clone Selection & Backup Banking", detail: "The CMC team assembles a clone selection scorecard with weighted criteria: qP (30%), aggregate %HMWS (20%), glycan profile (20%), metabolic efficiency (15%), growth rate (10%), HCP profile (5%). The highest-scored clone is designated the lead production clone. Two to three backup clones are designated simultaneously. All selected clones are immediately prioritized for pre-MCB expansion and cryopreservation. The selection rationale is documented in a formal selection report, which becomes part of the regulatory file and BLA." },
      { num: 8, title: "Initial Genetic Stability Assessment", detail: "Before committing to the MCB, 2–4 week genetic stability mini-studies are run for the lead clone: stability culture (serial passage without selection) followed by titer and CQA profiling at early, mid, and late passages. While this is not the full ICH Q5D study, it provides an early safety check against catastrophic instability. Clones showing >20% titer decline over 10 passages are flagged for re-evaluation." },
    ],
    duration: "12–20 weeks from stable pool to lead clone selection and initial banking",
    team: "Cell Line Development Scientists, Upstream Process Development, Analytical Development (CQA profiling), CMC Project Management",
    deliverables: [
      "Lead production clone with documented selection rationale",
      "2–3 backup clone candidates",
      "Clone selection report with full productivity + CQA profiling data",
      "ambr15 fed-batch performance data for all screened clones",
      "Initial CQA profile (glycans, aggregation, charge variants) for lead clone",
      "STR fingerprint of lead clone",
    ],
  },

  s04: {
    what: `Cell Banking is the act of preserving and protecting the lead production clone — converting it from a fragile laboratory cell culture into a precisely characterized, tested, and multiply redundant permanent biological archive. Every single commercial batch of the drug — for the next 20–30 years — will be manufactured starting from a single vial of the Master Cell Bank (MCB). This makes the MCB arguably the most valuable biological material in the entire program.\n\nThe MCB is prepared once and never again. Working Cell Banks (WCBs) are generated from MCB vials and used operationally for production campaigns. Both tiers require extensive characterization and testing to ensure safety, identity, purity, and stability. The testing program escalates from Phase 1 IND (a minimum safety panel) to BLA filing (a comprehensive viral safety, genetic identity, and tumorigenicity panel) following ICH Q5D.\n\nBeyond testing, the physical security of the cell banks is a manufacturing-critical priority. Cell banks are stored across geographically distributed sites in liquid nitrogen vapor phase, with redundant alarm monitoring, access controls, and defined chain-of-custody procedures. A single storage failure affecting an unbacked-up MCB would be catastrophic.`,
    before: `Receives from Stage 03: Lead production clone (and 2–3 backup clones) in active culture, clone selection report with documented selection rationale, and STR fingerprint.`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 05 (Upstream Development): Qualified Working Cell Bank vials ready for thaw and expansion into bioreactor seed trains. Also initiates the long-running cell bank testing programs required for IND and BLA.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Pre-MCB Expansion", detail: "The lead clone is expanded from its final CLD passage in a defined, documented expansion protocol. The goal is to generate 100–500 million cells in a healthy, high-viability, actively growing state. Cells must be in exponential growth phase at the time of banking to ensure maximum post-thaw recovery. Passage number from the original single-cell deposit is carefully tracked and documented throughout this expansion." },
      { num: 2, title: "MCB Preparation — Controlled-Rate Freezing", detail: "Cells are collected by centrifugation, resuspended at 10–20 × 10⁶ cells/mL in cryopreservation medium (10% DMSO in chemically defined basal media or with defined serum-free components), and dispensed into cryovials (typically 1 mL or 1.5 mL). Vials are loaded into a controlled-rate freezer (CRF) programmed for −1°C/min cooling from 4°C to −40°C, then transferred to vapor-phase liquid nitrogen storage at −140°C or below. Ramped freezing prevents ice crystal damage. MCB fill date, passage number, cell density, and CRF batch record are documented." },
      { num: 3, title: "MCB Post-Thaw Qualification", detail: "Representative MCB vials (2–5% of the lot, minimum 3 vials) are thawed and assessed: post-thaw viability (target ≥80% by trypan blue exclusion), recovery time to reach target VCD, and growth slope vs. historical data. Vials are also assessed for identity (STR profiling confirmation) and sterility. Only after qualification is the MCB lot approved for use." },
      { num: 4, title: "MCB Storage Across Multiple Sites", detail: "The MCB lot is distributed across at least 2 (best practice: 3) geographically separate storage locations: the manufacturing site's liquid nitrogen farm, an off-site long-term archive (often a specialized bio-repository), and a second off-site location in a different geographic region (earthquake/disaster redundancy). An inventory management system (IMS) tracks every vial, location, and withdrawal event. Temperature alarms at each site are qualified and monitored 24/7." },
      { num: 5, title: "MCB Characterization Testing — Phase 1 IND Panel", detail: "The Phase 1 IND requires a minimum testing panel: sterility by USP <71> culture method (14-day incubation), mycoplasma by USP <63> culture method (28-day) plus rapid PCR confirmation, in vitro adventitious agent testing (inoculation of indicator cell lines — MRC-5, Vero, MEF — with 14-day observation), identity by STR profiling or isoenzyme analysis, and cell counting/viability. This panel takes 6–8 weeks to complete and must be initiated immediately after MCB preparation." },
      { num: 6, title: "WCB Generation", detail: "After MCB qualification, 1–3 MCB vials are thawed, expanded through a defined number of passages, and used to prepare the Working Cell Bank (WCB). WCBs typically contain 50–200 vials at similar cell density to the MCB. WCB testing is an abbreviated version of MCB testing (sterility, mycoplasma, identity, viability) since the WCB is derived from the already-characterized MCB. WCBs are the operational resource — manufacturing pulls WCB vials for each production campaign seed train." },
      { num: 7, title: "Full MCB Testing — BLA Panel (Concurrent with Development)", detail: "ICH Q5D mandates a comprehensive BLA MCB testing package that takes 12–18 months to complete and therefore must begin early in development: in vivo adventitious agent testing (mice, guinea pigs, embryonated eggs — 28-day studies), retrovirus testing by S+L- assay and PERT (product-enhanced reverse transcriptase), TEM for retroviral particle enumeration, species-specific viral agents (reovirus-like agent for CHO), karyology (chromosomal analysis), and tumorigenicity. This panel is a critical-path BLA activity." },
      { num: 8, title: "Backup Clone Banking (Contingency)", detail: "Simultaneously, the 2–3 backup clones from Stage 03 are expanded and cryopreserved into backup MCBs using the same controlled-rate freezing protocol. Backup MCBs are stored but not fully characterized (partial characterization sufficient for contingency use). These provide the contingency against lead clone genetic instability, contamination, or catastrophic storage loss. The backup MCB strategy is documented in the IND CMC section." },
    ],
    duration: "8–16 weeks for MCB preparation and qualification; concurrent BLA testing program runs 12–18 months",
    team: "Cell Banking Operations, QC Microbiology, Analytical Development, CMC Regulatory, External viral safety testing labs",
    deliverables: [
      "Qualified Master Cell Bank (MCB) with lot release records",
      "Working Cell Bank (WCB) with post-thaw qualification data",
      "MCB Phase 1 IND testing report",
      "Cell bank storage locations and inventory management records",
      "Backup clone cryopreserved as contingency MCBs",
      "MCB BLA testing initiation plan with timeline",
    ],
  },

  s05: {
    what: `Upstream Process Development is where the bioreactor production process — the cell culture conditions, media, feeding strategy, and process controls — is designed, optimized, and characterized to reliably produce large quantities of high-quality drug substance. This is the stage where biology meets engineering: every decision about how cells are grown, fed, and harvested has direct consequences for productivity (titer), product quality (CQAs), and manufacturing economics (cost of goods).\n\nThe bioreactor is a precisely controlled environment: temperature, pH, dissolved oxygen, agitation, CO₂ stripping, and nutrient availability are all regulated. For fed-batch mAb processes, cells are grown for 12–18 days, consuming glucose and amino acids supplied by a feeding strategy, while secreting product. A typical commercial mAb process achieves 3–15 g/L titer and ~10–15 billion viable cell days of culture.\n\nA critical deliverable of this stage is the definition of Critical Process Parameters (CPPs) — those process inputs whose variability directly impacts CQAs. This classification requires mechanistic understanding (not just correlation) and is built through systematic Design of Experiments (DoE) studies. The CPP classification becomes a BLA commitment: CPPs must be monitored and controlled within defined ranges. This stage also develops and qualifies the Scale-Down Model (SDM), a small-scale bioreactor that faithfully mimics commercial scale and serves as the basis for all process characterization studies.`,
    before: `Receives from Stage 04: Qualified WCB vials ready for thaw and expansion. Also receives from Stage 01–03: preliminary QTPP, initial CQA list, and clone productivity/quality data from CLD. Early-stage media/process development may begin with transient material or stable pools before MCB banking is complete.`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 06 (Downstream): A defined, documented upstream process (media formulation, feeding strategy, bioreactor operating parameters, IPCs) producing consistent quality cell culture fluid (HCCF). Also delivers qualified SDM, initial CPP classification, and upstream control strategy elements to Stage 11 (Process Characterization).`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Cell Culture Media Development", detail: "Commercially available chemically defined media (CDM) platforms (BalanCD, CD CHO, EX-CELL) are used as starting points and customized through small-scale screening experiments. Key variables optimized: amino acid concentrations (glutamine, cysteine, tyrosine), lipid mixtures, trace metals (copper, zinc, iron, manganese — each with distinct glycosylation effects), vitamins, growth factors, and osmolality. Feed media (concentrated nutrient supplements added on days 3, 5, 7, 10, etc.) are similarly optimized to sustain cell growth and productivity throughout the fed-batch culture duration." },
      { num: 2, title: "Seed Train Development", detail: "The seed train is the sequential expansion process from a thawed WCB vial through spinner flasks, shake flasks, and inoculum bioreactors until enough cells are available to inoculate the production bioreactor. The seed train defines: thaw media, passage number at each stage, viable cell density (VCD) targets at each expansion step, passage intervals, and culture vessel formats. Seed train performance is critical — a seed train failure delays the production campaign and requires investigation." },
      { num: 3, title: "Fed-Batch Process Optimization", detail: "The production bioreactor parameters are optimized through one-factor-at-a-time (OFAT) experiments followed by DoE: inoculation VCD (typically 0.3–0.6 × 10⁶ cells/mL), feeding start day and schedule, feed volume per day, temperature shift point and target (often 37°C → 31–34°C around day 3–5 for productivity boost), pH setpoint and control deadband, dissolved oxygen setpoint (30–50% saturation), agitation (tip speed), and culture duration. These experiments generate titer + CQA data to identify optimal conditions." },
      { num: 4, title: "Glycosylation Control Strategy Development", detail: "Key upstream levers for glycan CQAs are identified and optimized: manganese sulfate supplementation (activates β-1,4-galactosyltransferase → increases galactosylation G1F/G2F); galactose supplementation (direct galactosylation substrate); copper depletion in media (reduces Golgi copper-dependent fucosyltransferase activity → decreases core fucosylation, increases ADCC-active afucosylated species); ammonia control (ammonia disrupts Golgi pH → inhibits sialylation and galactosylation); temperature effects on glycosyltransferase enzyme kinetics. For effector-function mAbs, the glycan CQA targets defined in the QTPP are used to guide media optimization." },
      { num: 5, title: "Scale-Down Model (SDM) Development & Qualification", detail: "A qualified 2–15L bioreactor scale-down model is developed to represent the commercial-scale process (typically 1,000–20,000L). Qualification requires matching key engineering parameters: kLa (oxygen mass transfer coefficient), CO₂ stripping profile, mixing time, temperature control uniformity, and sparger type. Comparability of CQA output (glycans, aggregation, charge variants, HCP) and process performance (titer, VCD, viability) between SDM and commercial scale is demonstrated with ≥3 side-by-side lots at each scale. All process characterization DoEs in Stage 11 will be conducted in this qualified SDM." },
      { num: 6, title: "In-Process Control (IPC) Definition", detail: "IPCs are in-process monitoring tests with defined action limits that trigger process adjustments or deviations during manufacturing. Upstream IPCs defined here: daily VCD and viability (Cedex or Vi-Cell automated analyzer), glucose concentration (target: maintain above 2 g/L), lactate (action limit: <3 g/L to ensure metabolic health), pH (confirm at-line vs. online probe reading), dissolved oxygen (confirm vs. setpoint), and osmolality (alert if >400 mOsm/kg). Action limits are set based on the development database and process characterization studies." },
      { num: 7, title: "Process Analytical Technology (PAT) Implementation", detail: "Where implemented, PAT provides real-time insight beyond manual sampling: Raman spectroscopy probes measure glucose, lactate, and glutamine in-line without sampling; capacitance probes estimate VCD continuously; dissolved CO₂ sensors monitor pCO₂ (a major scale-up challenge); near-IR probes characterize cell viability. PAT data is used for process monitoring, early deviation detection, and supports real-time release testing (RTRT) applications filed in the BLA." },
      { num: 8, title: "Harvest Process Development", detail: "After peak product accumulation (typically day 12–18 in fed-batch), the production bioreactor is harvested. Harvest strategy: temperature shift down (to reduce protease activity and prevent product degradation); centrifugation (disc-stack centrifuge at commercial scale, bench centrifuge at development scale) removes >99% of cells; depth filtration clarifies the centrate by removing cell debris, lipid droplets, and small particles. The clarified cell culture fluid (HCCF) is the input to downstream processing. Harvest conditions are optimized to maximize yield, protect product quality, and achieve turbidity targets for Protein A column loading." },
    ],
    duration: "12–24 months from initial media screening through SDM qualification and clinical supply generation",
    team: "Upstream Process Development Scientists, Bioprocess Engineers, Analytical Development, Media/Feed Formulation, Manufacturing Sciences",
    deliverables: [
      "Defined upstream process: media formulation, feed schedule, bioreactor parameters",
      "Qualified Scale-Down Model (SDM) with qualification report",
      "Initial CPP candidate list with preliminary classification",
      "Upstream IPC definitions with action limits",
      "Upstream process development report",
      "HCCF quality comparability data across development runs",
    ],
  },

  s06: {
    what: `Downstream Process Development designs the purification train — the series of chromatography, filtration, and concentration steps that converts the crude mixture of cells, media components, and secreted protein from the bioreactor harvest into highly purified, safe, and characterized drug substance. The starting material (clarified cell culture fluid, HCCF) contains the target protein at only 0.1–1% purity — the remaining 99%+ is everything from the host cell (HCPs, DNA, lipids, viruses) plus process chemicals. Downstream processing must achieve final purity >99% while simultaneously clearing viral safety risks, reducing HCP to <10 ng/mg, DNA to <10 ng/dose, and producing a drug substance suitable for human injection.\n\nFor monoclonal antibodies, the biopharmaceutical industry has converged on a remarkably conserved platform process: Protein A capture → Low pH viral inactivation → Ion exchange polishing → Viral filtration → UF/DF. This platform approach — applied to >80% of commercial mAbs — allows rapid development because each step's behavior is well-understood. However, the specific operating conditions for each step must be individually optimized and characterized for each molecule.\n\nViral clearance validation is a critical deliverable of this stage. ICH Q5A(R1) requires demonstrating virus removal through at least two orthogonal mechanisms, tested using model viruses across the spectrum of morphology and size. The BLA includes detailed viral clearance reports that must demonstrate sufficient safety margins for non-enveloped viruses (the hardest to clear).`,
    before: `Receives from Stage 05: Clarified cell culture fluid (HCCF) from the harvest process, with defined upstream conditions, and initial CQA characterization data from development batches.`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 07/08 (Analytical/Formulation): Purified drug substance (DS) at target concentration in the UF/DF buffer, with documented clearance of process-related (HCP, DNA, Protein A leachate) and product-related (aggregates, charge variants) impurities. Also delivers viral clearance validation data to Stage 12 (Process Validation).`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Harvest Clarification", detail: "The first downstream operation removes cells and large cell debris from the bioreactor harvest. At commercial scale: disk-stack centrifuge (20,000–60,000 g) removes >99% of cells in a continuous flow operation; depth filtration (typically two stages — 3–8 µm + 0.2 µm absolute-rated filter) removes residual cell debris, lipid droplets, and sub-micron particles. The output is clarified HCCF (cHCCF). Critical parameters: centrifuge bowl speed, flow rate, backpressure. Depth filter capacity (liters per m²) is a key economic parameter evaluated during development." },
      { num: 2, title: "Protein A Affinity Capture Chromatography", detail: "The cornerstone of mAb purification. Protein A (a bacterial surface protein from Staphylococcus aureus, now recombinantly produced) binds selectively to the Fc region of IgG antibodies with Kd ~5–10 nM. The cHCCF is loaded onto the Protein A column at neutral pH (7.0–7.4); impurities (HCPs, DNA, media components) pass through or are washed away; the mAb is eluted with low pH buffer (pH 2.8–3.5). Protein A achieves 99%+ selectivity for mAbs — a single step transforming 0.1% purity to 95%+ purity. Commercial resins: MabSelect SuRe, Praesto Jetted A50, CaptivA. Critical parameters: loading density (g mAb per L resin), wash conditions, elution pH, strip conditions. Resin reuse lifecycle (100–200 cycles) is validated and filed in the BLA." },
      { num: 3, title: "Low pH Viral Inactivation (VI)", detail: "Immediately after Protein A elution, the eluate pool is held at low pH (pH 3.4–3.7) for ≥60 minutes at room temperature. This step provides ≥4–5 log reduction factor (LRF) for enveloped viruses (MuLV model) by disrupting the lipid envelope. Critical parameters: pH setpoint (must be ≤3.7 for validated virus kill), hold time (must be ≥60 min), temperature (15–25°C), protein concentration (dilution during VI affects pH). Any pH excursion above the upper validated limit constitutes a potential viral safety concern requiring 21 CFR 312.32 safety reporting. After hold, the pool is neutralized to pH 5.0–6.0 before the next step." },
      { num: 4, title: "Cation Exchange (CEX) Polishing", detail: "CEX chromatography in bind-elute mode captures the mAb at low pH/conductivity (buffer: 50 mM acetate pH 5.0, <10 mS/cm) and resolves it from: aggregates (bind more tightly — harder to elute in the main fraction), acidic/basic charge variants (eluted at different salt concentrations), residual HCPs, and remaining DNA. Elution is by increasing salt gradient or step. The main peak fraction is collected with defined pooling criteria (UV absorbance slope). CEX is the primary polishing step for aggregate removal. Critical parameters: load pH, conductivity, elution salt concentration, pool limits." },
      { num: 5, title: "Anion Exchange (AEX) Flow-Through Polishing", detail: "AEX in flow-through mode exploits the fact that at mildly alkaline pH (7.0–8.0), the mAb carries a neutral or slightly positive charge and passes through the negatively charged resin, while DNA (highly negatively charged), endotoxin, and viruses bind and are retained. This 'negative purification' step provides ≥2–3 LRF for viruses and reduces DNA to <1 ng/dose. Critical parameters: load pH, conductivity, flow rate, resin load challenge. Common resins: Q Sepharose, Capto Q, Mustang Q membrane adsorbers. Membrane adsorbers (Mustang Q) offer high flow rates and single-use compatibility." },
      { num: 6, title: "Virus Filtration", detail: "A 20 nm-pore-size virus filter (Planova 20N, Viresolve Pro, Virosart CPV) provides ≥4 LRF specifically for small non-enveloped viruses (e.g., parvovirus MVM) — the hardest class to clear by other means. This is a size-exclusion mechanism: the 20 nm filter retains viruses (20–300 nm) while passing the mAb (~10 nm). Critical parameters: pressure (typically ≤30 psi), flux (L/m²/h), total throughput per filter (L/m² — defines filter sizing and cost). Plugging is the main risk — high aggregate load or HCP can foul filters prematurely. Virus filter sizing studies are validated at development scale." },
      { num: 7, title: "UF/DF — Concentration & Buffer Exchange", detail: "Ultrafiltration/diafiltration uses tangential flow filtration (TFF) with 10–30 kDa molecular weight cut-off membranes (polyethersulfone or regenerated cellulose). First, UF concentrates the mAb pool to an intermediate concentration (2–5×). Then diafiltration exchanges the buffer by diluting and concentrating repeatedly (7–10 diavolumes) to remove process buffer components and exchange into the formulation buffer composition (e.g., 25 mM histidine pH 6.0). Finally, the product is concentrated to the final DS target (10–200 mg/mL). Critical parameters: transmembrane pressure, crossflow velocity, concentration endpoint, final osmolality." },
      { num: 8, title: "Viral Clearance Validation Studies", detail: "In parallel with process development, viral clearance validation studies (scale-down model) demonstrate that the downstream process provides ≥12 log total LRF across two orthogonal mechanisms. ICH Q5A(R1) requires testing 4 model viruses: large enveloped retrovirus (MuLV — validates low pH VI), large non-enveloped (Reovirus-3), small non-enveloped (parvovirus MVM/B19 — the safety benchmark for viral filtration), and a site-specific virus. Each contributing step is spiked with high-titer virus stock and the LRF calculated. The viral clearance report is a required BLA submission document and is scrutinized by regulators." },
    ],
    duration: "12–24 months from initial process scouting through viral clearance validation and clinical supply generation",
    team: "Downstream Process Development, Viral Clearance Scientists, Analytical Development, CMC Regulatory",
    deliverables: [
      "Defined downstream purification process with all operating parameters",
      "Viral clearance validation reports (ICH Q5A compliant)",
      "Protein A resin lifetime study (preliminary)",
      "Impurity clearance data: HCP, DNA, Protein A leachate, endotoxin",
      "Scale-down model qualification for each DSP unit operation",
      "Drug substance specification (preliminary)",
    ],
  },

  s07: {
    what: `Analytical Development builds the complete measurement toolkit for the entire biologic program — every test that will ever be used to release a clinical or commercial batch, characterize the product, support process development, or detect manufacturing deviations. Without these methods, you cannot know whether the drug is safe, active, pure, or stable. Analytical Development is the scientific backbone of all downstream CMC activities.\n\nThe scope is vast: identity methods confirm the protein is the correct molecule (peptide mapping, LC-MS primary sequence); purity methods quantify aggregates (SEC-HPLC), fragments (CE-SDS), and charge variants (icIEF); potency assays measure biological activity relative to a reference standard (cell-based ADCC, receptor binding inhibition, or enzyme activity — depending on mechanism of action); safety methods detect endotoxin, mycoplasma, sterility, and particulates; characterization methods map every post-translational modification (glycosylation, deamidation, oxidation, disulfide bonds) using high-resolution mass spectrometry.\n\nEach method must be developed, then qualified for early clinical use, then fully validated per ICH Q2(R2) before Phase 3 and BLA filing. Method validation establishes statistical proof that the method measures what it claims to measure: specificity, linearity, range, precision, accuracy, quantitation limit, robustness. This is not optional — regulatory agencies will not accept BLA release data from non-validated methods.`,
    before: `Receives from Stages 05/06: Purified drug substance samples from development and clinical manufacturing runs. Receives from Stage 01: QTPP and initial CQA identification. Receives from Stages 05/06: Process characterization data identifying which attributes vary with process parameters and therefore need precise measurement.`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 10 (Clinical Manufacturing): Qualified methods for Phase 1 QC testing and batch release. Delivers to Stage 11/12 (PC/PV): Validated methods for process characterization and PPQ. Delivers to Stage 15 (BLA): Fully validated analytical package for Module 3. Also delivers reference standards, specification development, and stability-indicating methods to Stage 14 (Stability).`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "CQA Risk Assessment — FMEA-Based Approach", detail: "Using an FMEA framework, each quality attribute is scored by severity (clinical consequence if outside spec — immunogenicity, reduced efficacy, safety risk), occurrence (how often it's observed outside range), and detectability (can current tests catch it). Attributes scoring above a defined risk threshold become CQAs — those requiring controlled specifications, validated methods, and continuous monitoring. This formal risk assessment is required for QbD-compliant BLA submissions. Typical mAb CQAs: aggregation (HMWS%), fragments (LMWS%), main charge peak (icIEF), glycan profile (G0F/G1F/G2F/HMGN/afucosylated), potency (%RA), identity (peptide map), endotoxin, sterility, particulates." },
      { num: 2, title: "Identity Method Development — Peptide Mapping", detail: "The gold-standard identity method for biologics: tryptic digestion of the protein followed by RPLC-MS/MS analysis of the resulting peptides. Method development involves: protease selection (trypsin alone, or LysC + trypsin for enhanced coverage), denaturation/reduction/alkylation conditions, HPLC column/gradient optimization for peptide separation, and MS fragmentation parameters. The resulting peptide map provides ≥95% sequence coverage and serves as the primary structure identity confirmation. Modified peptides (deamidated, oxidized, glycosylated) are identified and characterized. This method evolves throughout development into a stability-indicating method and MAM platform." },
      { num: 3, title: "Purity Methods — SEC-HPLC & CE-SDS", detail: "SEC-HPLC is developed using a size-exclusion column (TSKgel G3000SWXL or similar) in native conditions (PBS pH 6.8–7.4). Method parameters optimized: column selection, mobile phase composition, flow rate, injection volume, run time. The method quantifies: main peak (%), HMWS (high molecular weight species — dimers, oligomers), and LMWS (low molecular weight species — fragments). CE-SDS (capillary electrophoresis with SDS) under reducing conditions resolves heavy and light chains and any clipping products; under non-reducing conditions shows intact IgG vs. non-covalent aggregates vs. fragments. These orthogonal methods detect complementary populations." },
      { num: 4, title: "Charge Variant Analysis — icIEF & CEX-HPLC", detail: "Imaged capillary isoelectric focusing (icIEF) separates protein species by isoelectric point (pI) under a pH gradient in a capillary coated to prevent electroosmotic flow. Method development: ampholyte selection, pI markers, focusing duration, UV wavelength. The icIEF chromatogram shows the acidic variants (C-terminal lysine clipping, deamidation), main peak, and basic variants (amidated C-terminus, glycation). For programs where charge variants are CQAs (deamidation in CDRs affecting potency), CEX-HPLC is developed as a complementary method with higher resolution for specific peaks." },
      { num: 5, title: "Glycan Analysis — UHPLC Fluorescence & MS", detail: "N-glycosylation is characterized by: (1) enzymatic release of N-glycans from the protein using PNGase F; (2) fluorescent labeling with 2-AB (2-aminobenzamide) or procainamide; (3) UHPLC separation with fluorescence detection; (4) glycan peak identification by glucose unit (GU) values, MS fragmentation, or glycan standards. The resulting profile reports: G0F%, G1F%, G2F%, Man5%, afucosylated%, sialylated%, and other glycan species. For mAbs with ADCC mechanism, afucosylation and galactosylation are direct CQAs. This method is used in both characterization and as a CPV monitoring tool for commercial lots." },
      { num: 6, title: "Potency Assay Development — MOA-Linked", detail: "FDA's 2008 Potency Guidance requires that the release potency assay reflect the molecule's mechanism of action (MOA). Development activities: (1) define which MOA to measure (ADCC, CDC, receptor binding, enzyme inhibition); (2) develop the assay format (NK cell-based cytotoxicity, Jurkat ADCC reporter, receptor binding ELISA, cell proliferation inhibition); (3) optimize assay conditions (cell density, antibody concentration range, incubation time); (4) establish relative potency format with reference standard. Cell-based assays require reference standards and system suitability criteria. Assay variability (CV) characterization drives specification design (typically 70–130% RA acceptance criteria)." },
      { num: 7, title: "Reference Standard Program", detail: "The reference standard is the benchmark against which all potency assays and many comparative analytical tests are measured. Development activities: selection of a representative lot as the primary reference standard; extensive characterization of the primary reference (full panel of CQA methods); preparation as frozen aliquots at defined concentration and formulation; shelf life determination by ongoing real-time and accelerated stability; secondary reference standard preparation when primary is depleted. The reference standard is a BLA-registered material — changes require bridging studies and regulatory notification." },
      { num: 8, title: "Method Qualification (Phase 1) and Full Validation (Phase 3/BLA)", detail: "Phase 1 IND: Methods are 'qualified' — a subset of validation parameters (specificity, precision, linearity) is demonstrated to show fitness for clinical use. Full validation per ICH Q2(R2) is performed before Phase 3 start and completed before BLA: specificity, linearity, range, accuracy, precision (repeatability, intermediate precision, reproducibility), limit of detection (LoD), limit of quantitation (LoQ), and robustness. For biological assays, ICH Q2 is supplemented with relative potency/reportable value framework validation. Validation reports are required BLA submission documents." },
    ],
    duration: "Continuous throughout the program; initial method development 6–12 months; full validation completed 12–18 months before BLA filing",
    team: "Analytical Development Scientists, QC Analytical, Bioassay Development, Reference Standard Management, Method Validation",
    deliverables: [
      "CQA risk assessment report (FMEA-based)",
      "Qualified analytical methods package for Phase 1 IND",
      "Validated analytical methods package for BLA (ICH Q2(R2) compliant)",
      "Reference standard: primary lot with characterization package",
      "Potency assay with relative potency format and validated",
      "Stability-indicating method panel",
    ],
  },

  s08: {
    what: `Formulation Development designs the final drug product — the physical presentation of the molecule that patients or clinicians will actually use. A monoclonal antibody is not a drug product until it is formulated: dissolved in the right buffer, at the right concentration, with the right excipients to maintain stability, packaged in a container that protects it from light and oxygen, and labeled with a shelf life supported by real-time stability data.\n\nFormulation development must solve a fundamental challenge: protein molecules are inherently unstable. Left to their own devices, proteins aggregate (fold together → form particles → visible aggregates), oxidize (methionine, tryptophan residues damaged by reactive oxygen species), deamidate (asparagine spontaneously converts to aspartate, changing charge), or fragment. Each of these degradation pathways creates impurities with immunogenicity risk. The formulation must kinetically suppress all these degradation routes for 18–36 months on the shelf.\n\nModern formulation development uses high-throughput screening: dozens of buffer/excipient combinations are screened simultaneously using thermal stability (DSF/DSC Tm), intrinsic fluorescence (stability), dynamic light scattering (aggregation), and accelerated stability (40°C/1-week). The winning formulation is then confirmed in the final container-closure system and subjected to full ICH Q5C/Q1A stability protocols.`,
    before: `Receives from Stage 06: Purified drug substance in development buffer (UF/DF output). Receives from Stage 07: CQA definitions (what attributes must be protected), stability-indicating analytical methods. Receives from Stage 01: QTPP (target dosage form, route of administration, concentration, and shelf-life goals).`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 09/10 (Tech Transfer/Clinical Manufacturing): Final formulation composition (buffer, excipients, concentration), container-closure system specification, and drug product manufacturing process. Delivers to Stage 14 (Stability): Formal stability studies started on development and clinical lots. Delivers to Stage 15 (BLA): Formulation development report, container-closure compatibility data, extractables/leachables data.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Preformulation Characterization", detail: "Before screening formulation conditions, the molecule is characterized physically and chemically: pI (isoelectric point) determines the pH range where the molecule has minimum charge and maximum colloidal stability (typically formulated 1–2 pH units below pI); intrinsic viscosity at high concentration is measured (critical for SC formulations); colloidal stability by dynamic light scattering (DLS) second virial coefficient (B22) or interaction parameter (kD) across pH/salt conditions; aggregation propensity by SEC at multiple concentrations; thermal unfolding by differential scanning calorimetry (DSC) gives Tm values as a baseline." },
      { num: 2, title: "Buffer and pH Screening", detail: "A DoE screens 3–5 buffer types (histidine, acetate, citrate, succinate, phosphate) across pH 4.5–7.5 in a matrix format. Each condition is assessed by DSF (fluorescence-based thermal stability Tm), DLS (particle size and polydispersity), and SEC-HPLC after 1-week at 40°C (accelerated degradation). Histidine buffers (pH 5.5–6.5) are most commonly selected for mAbs due to buffering capacity, low viscosity contribution, cryoprotective properties, and antioxidant activity. The optimal pH balances chemical stability (lower pH reduces deamidation, higher pH reduces aggregation) against oxidation risk." },
      { num: 3, title: "Excipient Screening — Stabilizers, Surfactants, Tonicity Agents", detail: "Key excipient classes screened: (1) Stabilizers — sucrose (0.1–10%) and trehalose provide cryoprotection and lyoprotection by preferential exclusion mechanism; (2) Surfactants — polysorbate 20 (PS20) or polysorbate 80 (PS80) at 0.01–0.05% prevent surface-induced aggregation during processing and shipping; (3) Tonicity agents — NaCl or sucrose adjust osmolality to 270–330 mOsm/kg (iso-osmotic for IV/SC); (4) Antioxidants — methionine (1–5 mM) scavenges peroxides and protects Met/Trp residues from oxidation; (5) Chelators — EDTA (0.01–0.05 mM) sequesters metal ions that catalyze oxidation. High-throughput DSF screens rank hundreds of combinations simultaneously." },
      { num: 4, title: "High-Concentration Formulation Development (SC Products)", detail: "Subcutaneous products require concentrations >100 mg/mL (limited injection volume: 1.5–2 mL max for SC). At high concentration, viscosity increases dramatically (can exceed 100 cP at 200 mg/mL — uncomfortable and potentially impossible to inject). Viscosity reduction strategies: arginine additions (breaks hydrophobic and electrostatic interactions), pH optimization, ionic strength adjustment, hyaluronan co-formulation. SC bioavailability (~70–85%) and injection site tolerability are assessed. Formulation DoEs specifically optimize the viscosity vs. stability trade-off at commercial concentration." },
      { num: 5, title: "Container-Closure System (CCS) Selection", detail: "CCS choice determines the drug product presentation: clear glass vials (Type I borosilicate) for most biologics, pre-filled syringes (PFS) or cartridges for auto-injector combination products. Key CCS development activities: glass type qualification (Type I requirement — lowest extractables), stopper/closure testing (compatibility, particle shedding, integrity), silicone oil characterization (siliconized barrels in PFS are a known source of sub-visible particles triggering immunogenicity concern), tungsten assessment (tungsten residue from glass forming process can aggregate proteins), headspace oxygen assessment (photooxidation and oxidative degradation). ICH Q3E (2024) defines the extractables/leachables safety assessment framework." },
      { num: 6, title: "Lyophilization Process Development (If Applicable)", detail: "For products requiring lyophilization (liquid instability, ultra-low concentration, or extreme shelf-life requirements): formulation optimization for lyophilizability (collapse temperature Tc > primary drying shelf temperature); lyophilization cycle development (shelf temperature ramp rates for freezing, primary drying chamber pressure and temperature optimization to maximize sublimation rate while maintaining product below Tc, secondary drying temperature ramp for residual moisture removal to <1%); cake characterization (appearance, reconstitution time ≤5 min, residual moisture, reconstituted protein quality). Lyophilizer mapping and cycle qualification are performed." },
      { num: 7, title: "Photostability and Forced Degradation Studies", detail: "ICH Q1B photostability testing exposes the drug product to light (cool white fluorescent + near UV fluorescent) to demonstrate whether light protection (amber vials, secondary packaging) is required and what photodegradation pathways are relevant. Forced degradation studies (acid/base hydrolysis, oxidative stress with H₂O₂ or metal catalysts, thermal stress, agitation stress, freeze-thaw cycling) identify the degradation products, characterize them using mass spectrometry, and confirm the stability-indicating methods detect each degradation pathway. This data goes into the degradation pathway section of the BLA." },
      { num: 8, title: "ICH Q5C Stability Program Initiation", detail: "The formal ICH Q5C/Q1A(R2) stability program begins with the first GMP lots of drug product. Conditions: 25°C/60% RH (long-term), 40°C/75% RH (accelerated), 5°C (refrigerated, as appropriate), −20°C (frozen). Real-time study duration continues until the proposed shelf-life claim is supported (typically 18–24 months real-time for a 24-month shelf life). The drug product shelf life is determined by the attribute first approaching its specification limit under long-term conditions — typically aggregation or potency." },
    ],
    duration: "12–24 months for full formulation development; initial formulation for Phase 1 typically 6–9 months",
    team: "Formulation Development Scientists, Physical Chemistry, Container-Closure Specialists, Device Engineering (SC products), Stability Sciences",
    deliverables: [
      "Final drug product formulation composition (buffer, pH, excipients, concentration)",
      "Container-closure system qualification data",
      "Preformulation characterization package",
      "Extractables/leachables risk assessment (ICH Q3E)",
      "ICH Q5C stability protocol and initial time point data",
      "Lyophilization cycle (if applicable)",
    ],
  },

  s09: {
    what: `Technology Transfer (Tech Transfer) is the organized, documented, and technically validated process of moving the biologic drug manufacturing process from the process development laboratory into a GMP manufacturing facility where clinical or commercial batches will actually be made. It is one of the highest-risk stages in the program: the process must perform reliably in a new environment, with different equipment, different operators, and different raw material supply chains, producing drug of identical quality to what was developed.\n\nTech transfer is not simply handing over a document package. It requires the receiving site to fully understand not just the 'what' (process steps, parameters) but the 'why' (mechanistic understanding of each CPP-CQA relationship), the 'what-if' (contingency procedures for deviations), and the 'how' (equipment-specific implementation details). Analytical method transfers are equally complex — the same method must produce statistically equivalent results on different instruments, by different analysts, using locally qualified reagents.\n\nA failed tech transfer run — where the GMP batch fails a critical CQA — can delay a clinical supply campaign by 3–6 months. Given clinical trial schedules, this may delay first-in-human dosing by the same amount. Technology transfer planning, risk assessment, and proactive gap analysis are therefore CMC critical-path activities.`,
    before: `Receives from Stages 05/06/07/08: Complete process development package including process description, batch records (draft), analytical methods, reference standards, and development data. Receives from Stage 04: Qualified WCBs for the manufacturing site cell bank. Receives from Stage 03: Clone characterization and banking data.`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 10 (Clinical Manufacturing): A GMP-ready manufacturing site with demonstrated process and analytical capability, trained operators, qualified equipment, and a batch record approved for cGMP manufacture. Also initiates the regulatory filing process (IND CMC section updates) documenting the manufacturing site.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Technology Transfer Gap Assessment", detail: "The sending site (process development) and receiving site (manufacturing) conduct a structured gap analysis comparing: equipment train (bioreactor model, type, instrumentation), facility class (ISO classification, HVAC design), analytical instruments (HPLC systems, mass spectrometers, bioassay equipment), utility specifications (water for injection, purified water, compressed gases), raw material supply chains, and operating procedures. Each gap is risk-assessed and a mitigation plan documented. Common gaps: bioreactor vendor/model differences (requiring mixing time re-characterization), HPLC system differences (requiring method bridge experiments), local reagent/standard preparation differences." },
      { num: 2, title: "Knowledge Transfer Package (KTP) Preparation", detail: "The sending site prepares a comprehensive KTP: process description with mechanistic background for each step, development history summary (key decisions and their rationale), CPP classification with supporting data, scale-up parameters (kLa, mixing time, sparger type), analytical method package with validation data and reference materials, batch record template, in-process control definitions, cleaning and sanitization procedures, and known process sensitivities ('watch-outs' for manufacturing teams). The KTP is a living document updated during transfer execution." },
      { num: 3, title: "Equipment Qualification at Receiving Site", detail: "Manufacturing equipment must be qualified per FDA/EMA expectations: Installation Qualification (IQ) confirms equipment installed per vendor specification and site design; Operational Qualification (OQ) confirms equipment operates within its specified parameters across its operational range (bioreactor pH control, temperature uniformity, DO probe calibration, sparger integrity); Performance Qualification (PQ) demonstrates the equipment performs consistently in the intended process context. Bioreactor qualification includes mixing time studies, kLa determination, and heat transfer characterization. HPLC and other analytical instruments undergo analytical instrument qualification (AIQ) per USP <1058>." },
      { num: 4, title: "Analytical Method Transfer", detail: "Each QC method used for release, stability, or in-process testing must be formally transferred from the development or sending-site laboratory to the receiving site. ICH Q2(R2) provides the framework. Method transfer verification experiments: the receiving site performs the method in parallel with the sending site on identical split samples. Statistical acceptance criteria (equivalence testing, % difference limits) are pre-defined and must be met before the method is 'released' for GMP use. Biological assays (potency) require additional system suitability demonstration. Reference standards are shipped with documented chain-of-custody." },
      { num: 5, title: "Draft Batch Record Preparation & Review", detail: "The process development team drafts the GMP-executable batch records using the site's batch record template format. Each manufacturing step is documented: materials list with specifications, equipment list with qualified identifiers, procedural steps with explicit parameter targets and action limits, sampling plan with IPC specifications, and signature/date blocks for operators and reviewers. Batch records undergo multi-functional review (Manufacturing, QA, Regulatory, Technical) and are approved in the electronic batch record (eBR) or paper system before engineering runs begin." },
      { num: 6, title: "Engineering (Non-GMP) Runs at Receiving Site", detail: "One to three engineering runs are conducted at the receiving site under non-GMP (or GMP-like) conditions to confirm the process performs equivalently to the development scale. Engineering runs identify equipment-specific adjustments: bioreactor probe calibration corrections, media prep sequence variations, depth filter flush volumes, chromatography equilibration time adjustments. CQA data from engineering runs is compared against the development database. Engineering runs generate material for analytical method transfer experiments and may produce material for safety/toxicology studies." },
      { num: 7, title: "Regulatory Filing — Site Establishment in IND/BLA", detail: "The manufacturing site must be registered in the regulatory filing before GMP clinical supply batches can be made. For Phase 1 IND: a CMC amendment is filed (30-day FDA review) listing the manufacturing site, process description, analytical testing locations, and batch release procedures. For BLA: detailed site information, validation data, and a description of all manufacturing equipment is included. International filings (EMA, PMDA) have additional site-specific requirements. The site must have a current cGMP compliance profile (no outstanding Warning Letters or import alerts)." },
      { num: 8, title: "GMP Readiness Review & Release Authorization", detail: "Before the first GMP campaign, a formal GMP readiness review is conducted: all SOPs reviewed and approved; all equipment qualified; all personnel trained (with training records in the learning management system); raw materials tested and released; reference standards issued from the reference standard program; batch records approved; QC methods qualified/validated; facility qualification documents complete; cleaning validation data (if applicable) reviewed. A signed GMP readiness checklist authorizes the start of the first GMP production campaign." },
    ],
    duration: "6–18 months depending on site complexity, equipment gaps, and number of methods transferred",
    team: "Tech Transfer Teams (sending + receiving), Manufacturing Sciences, QC, QA, Regulatory Affairs, CMO (if applicable)",
    deliverables: [
      "Tech Transfer Gap Assessment with risk mitigation plan",
      "Knowledge Transfer Package (KTP)",
      "Equipment qualification reports (IQ/OQ/PQ)",
      "Analytical method transfer reports",
      "Approved GMP batch records",
      "Engineering run data confirming process comparability",
      "IND CMC amendment registering manufacturing site",
    ],
  },

  s10: {
    what: `Clinical Manufacturing is the execution of actual GMP production campaigns to supply drug product for clinical trials — Phase 1 safety studies, Phase 2 dose-finding, and Phase 3 pivotal efficacy trials. Each phase has different scale, batch size, and regulatory documentation requirements, but all clinical supply is made under current Good Manufacturing Practice (cGMP) regulations that govern facilities, equipment, materials, personnel, documentation, and quality systems.\n\nPhase 1 batches are typically small (50–500L bioreactor scale), made at a clinical manufacturing facility or contract manufacturing organization (CMO), and need to supply perhaps 20–100 patients in a first-in-human study. Phase 3 batches are made at or close to commercial scale (2,000–20,000L) and must be able to supply hundreds or thousands of patients across multiple clinical sites globally, often for 2–3 years of trial duration.\n\nEvery clinical batch has a documented lineage: from WCB vial thaw through seed train, production bioreactor, downstream purification, formulation, fill-finish, QC testing, and final batch release. The batch record documents every action taken, every measurement made, and every deviation encountered. The batch cannot be released to clinical investigators until QC testing is complete and the QA/QP team formally releases the batch. In the EU, a Qualified Person (QP) must personally certify each clinical batch before shipment to patients.`,
    before: `Receives from Stage 09: GMP-ready manufacturing site with approved batch records, qualified equipment, trained personnel, and released raw materials. Receives from Stage 04: WCB vials for the production facility. Receives from Stage 08: Approved drug product formulation and container-closure system.`,
    after: `Delivers drug product to the clinical supply chain for distribution to clinical trial sites. Also generates manufacturing data (batch records, in-process data, CQA results) that: contributes to the process development database, triggers comparability assessments when process changes occur, and forms the foundation of the process validation PPQ historical data package.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Campaign Planning & Materials Procurement", detail: "Each GMP manufacturing campaign begins with a production order and campaign plan: WCB vial assignment (specific lot and vial numbers assigned to this campaign), raw material ordering and receipt (bioreactor media, chromatography buffers, filters, single-use components), reagent preparation schedule, equipment scheduling, QC testing schedule, and batch record issuance. Raw materials are released by QC against established specifications before use. Single-use system integrity testing is performed before each bioreactor campaign. Lead times for critical raw materials (Protein A resin, viral filters) must be planned 8–12 weeks in advance." },
      { num: 2, title: "Seed Train — Cell Expansion", detail: "A WCB vial is thawed in a defined thaw media at 37°C, transferred to a small shake flask, and sequentially expanded through increasing vessel sizes (T-flask → spinner flask → 3L → 10L → 50–200L seed bioreactor) over 7–14 days following the seed train batch record precisely. At each passage, VCD, viability, and passage number are documented. Growth rate is compared against historical reference data — significant deviations trigger an investigation before inoculating the production bioreactor." },
      { num: 3, title: "Production Bioreactor Run", detail: "The production bioreactor (50–20,000L depending on clinical phase) is inoculated at the defined VCD, and the 12–18 day fed-batch culture proceeds per the batch record. In-process controls are measured and documented daily: VCD (Cedex/Vi-Cell), viability, glucose, lactate, pH (offline + online), DO (online), osmolality, and where applicable pCO₂. Feeding steps (bolus or continuous pump addition) follow the defined schedule. Temperature shifts, if part of the process, are executed at the defined time points. Any in-process result outside action limits generates an in-process deviation requiring investigation before proceeding." },
      { num: 4, title: "Harvest", detail: "At the defined end-of-culture criteria (viability <60% OR day 14 of culture, whichever first, for example), the production bioreactor is harvested. Disk-stack centrifuge removes cells, followed by depth filtration to clarify the HCCF. In-process samples are taken for pre-harvest titer, viability, and pre-filter vs. post-filter turbidity confirmation. The clarified HCCF is transferred to the purification suite. Harvest yield and turbidity are documented in the batch record." },
      { num: 5, title: "Drug Substance (DS) Purification Campaign", detail: "The downstream purification train runs in sequence: Protein A capture, viral inactivation (pH hold documented with time, pH, and temperature logs to confirm compliance with validated parameters), CEX polishing, AEX flow-through, viral filtration, and UF/DF concentration to target. Each chromatography step has column preparation, equilibration, loading, washing, and elution steps documented in the batch record. Pool samples are taken after each step and measured for titer (yield tracking), pH, conductivity, turbidity, and selected CQAs. Final DS is filtered through a 0.22 µm sterilizing-grade filter into a pre-qualified product contact container and stored frozen (−70°C) pending QC testing." },
      { num: 6, title: "Drug Product (DP) Fill-Finish Manufacturing", detail: "DS is thawed, diluted to target concentration, filtered, and filled into primary containers (vials, syringes) in an aseptic environment (ISO 5 laminar flow cabinet or isolator, within an ISO 7 background). Fill weight/volume accuracy is confirmed by gravimetric or volumetric measurement. Sterile filtration through 0.22 µm bioburden-reducing + sterilizing-grade filter train is documented. For lyophilized products, filled vials are transferred to the lyophilizer and the lyophilization cycle executed per the validated process. Vials are stoppered, capped (crimp seal or flip-off cap), and labeled with batch number, expiry (tentative), and identification." },
      { num: 7, title: "QC Testing — Release Panel", detail: "Each clinical lot undergoes a comprehensive QC release test panel before any batch disposition decision. Tests: appearance (visual inspection for particles, color, clarity), identity (peptide mapping or specific HPLC), purity (SEC-HPLC for aggregation; CE-SDS for fragments), potency (cell-based or binding assay vs. reference standard), protein concentration (A280 or ELISA), pH, osmolality, sub-visible particles (USP <787> MFI/light obscuration), sterility (USP <71> 14-day culture), endotoxin (LAL kinetic turbidimetric), mycoplasma (PCR + culture for DS), residual moisture (for lyophilized). Out-of-specification (OOS) results trigger immediate investigation." },
      { num: 8, title: "Batch Disposition & IMP Release", detail: "After all QC tests pass, the batch record is reviewed by the QA team for completeness, accuracy, and compliance. All deviations from the batch record are assessed for impact on product quality (and documented as closed investigations or risks accepted). The QA/QP releases the batch by signing the Certificate of Analysis (CoA) and batch disposition record. The batch number, lot size, test results, and release date are entered into the batch management system. For EU supply, the QP certifies the batch per EU Clinical Trial Directive requirements. The IMP (Investigational Medicinal Product) is then transferred to clinical supply chain for distribution to clinical sites." },
    ],
    duration: "8–16 weeks per batch campaign (seed train + production + DS + DP + QC); Phase 3 campaigns may produce multiple batches in parallel",
    team: "GMP Manufacturing Operators, Manufacturing Sciences, QC Analytical, QA, QP (EU), Clinical Supply Chain, Regulatory Affairs",
    deliverables: [
      "Completed batch records for all GMP lots",
      "Certificates of Analysis (CoA) for each released batch",
      "Batch disposition records",
      "Manufacturing deviations and investigation reports",
      "In-process data summary for process development database",
      "Clinical supply shipped to trial sites",
    ],
  },

  s11: {
    what: `Process Characterization (PC) is the scientific deep-dive that transforms process development knowledge into a formally validated, regulatory-filed understanding of how process parameters affect product quality. It is primarily conducted in Scale-Down Models (SDMs) using designed experiments (DoEs), and its outputs — the CPP classification, the design space definition, and the process control strategy — are the core of Module 3.2.S.2.2 in the BLA.\n\nThe central deliverable is CPP classification: for every process parameter (upstream: pH, temperature, DO, feeding rate; downstream: load density, elution pH, hold times), the team must classify it as Critical (a CPP — impacts a CQA), Key (a KPP — impacts performance but not CQA quality), or Non-Key (no significant impact within studied range). This classification requires more than correlation — it requires statistical confidence and mechanistic understanding. Under-classification (missing a true CPP) means that parameter can drift uncontrolled in commercial manufacturing, potentially causing CQA failures years later.\n\nProcess characterization is one of the most resource-intensive stages in CMC — involving hundreds of small-scale experiments, dozens of analytical tests per run, and months of data analysis. It typically begins in Phase 2 and must be complete before Phase 3 clinical batches begin, ensuring the commercial-scale process being validated in Phase 3 is fully characterized.`,
    before: `Receives from Stage 05/06: Qualified SDMs for upstream and downstream unit operations, a preliminary process parameter list, and development data suggesting which parameters may be influential. Receives from Stage 07: Validated analytical methods capable of detecting CQA changes at the level relevant to clinical impact.`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 12 (Process Validation): CPP classification report, design space definition, control strategy (NORs, PARs, and CPP monitoring requirements), and a validated SDM confirmed equivalent to commercial scale. This package directly informs the PPQ protocol design.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Risk Assessment — Parameter Identification & Prioritization", detail: "A formal risk assessment (FMEA or Ishikawa diagram) identifies all potential process parameters for each unit operation. Parameters are rated by severity (impact if out of range), occurrence (probability of drifting), and detectability (ability to monitor). High-risk parameters advance to characterization studies as factors; lower-risk parameters are evaluated through targeted experiments. Typically 30–80 parameters are identified across upstream + downstream, of which 10–20 are selected for DoE characterization. The risk assessment document is a required BLA appendix." },
      { num: 2, title: "SDM Representativeness Confirmation", detail: "Before running characterization DoEs, the SDM (2–15L bioreactor or scaled-down chromatography column) must be confirmed as representative of commercial scale. Representativeness criteria: key CQAs (glycans, aggregation, charge variants) are within ±X% of commercial scale; process performance (titer, yield, impurity levels) falls within ±Y% of the commercial range. A minimum of 3 side-by-side SDM vs. commercial lots supports the qualification. If gaps exist, SDM conditions are adjusted to match commercial behavior before characterization begins." },
      { num: 3, title: "Univariate (OFAT) Screening Studies", detail: "One-factor-at-a-time studies provide preliminary estimates of parameter effect size and direction. Each candidate parameter is varied individually across a range (e.g., bioreactor pH 6.8 → 7.4 in 0.2 pH steps) while all other parameters are held at their nominal values. Response data (CQAs + yield) are plotted. Parameters showing negligible effects across their full plausible range (effect size < assay method variability) may be classified as non-key parameters without requiring a full DoE. Parameters with clear or ambiguous effects advance to the DoE stage." },
      { num: 4, title: "Design of Experiments (DoE) Execution", detail: "Multivariate DoEs study multiple parameters simultaneously, capturing main effects and interactions. DoE designs used: fractional factorial designs (screening, 2^(k-p)) for initial factor screening; full factorial designs for factors with expected interactions; central composite designs (CCD) or Box-Behnken designs for response surface modeling to define a design space. DoE execution follows a randomized run order to minimize systematic bias. Each experimental run is fully executed at SDM scale with complete in-process sampling. Typically 20–50 DoE runs per unit operation characterization package." },
      { num: 5, title: "CPP Classification Statistical Analysis", detail: "DoE data is analyzed using statistical software (JMP, Minitab, SAS). Significance testing (ANOVA, regression) determines which main effects and interactions are statistically significant. For CPP classification: a parameter is CPP if its effect on a CQA is statistically significant AND the effect size is clinically meaningful (exceeds a pre-defined threshold linked to clinical relevance of the CQA). Classification cutoffs are defined in the characterization protocol before analysis (pre-specification prevents bias). The final classification (CPP/KPP/non-key) for each parameter is reported with the supporting statistical data." },
      { num: 6, title: "Normal Operating Range (NOR) and Proven Acceptable Range (PAR) Definition", detail: "For CPPs, two ranges are defined: the PAR is the wider range demonstrated by characterization data to produce acceptable CQA output (supported by DoE data and mechanistic understanding); the NOR is the tighter commercial operating range providing a 'guard band' inside the PAR. The gap between NOR and PAR is the buffer allowing minor process variation without risk. For non-CPPs, PARs are still defined but their exceedance doesn't require a regulatory change. Design space (the multidimensional combination of PARs) is defined and filed in the BLA — operating within it doesn't require a regulatory submission." },
      { num: 7, title: "Control Strategy Development", detail: "The control strategy describes how each CPP will be controlled, monitored, and measured during commercial manufacturing. Elements: parameter set points (NOR midpoint targets), control technology (PID controllers, cascade control, feed-forward control), monitoring frequency (continuous online vs. daily at-line), alarm and action limits (operator intervention thresholds), in-process controls (IPCs) with acceptance criteria, and test linkages to specifications. The control strategy is summarized in the BLA in a process control table and referenced throughout the submission." },
      { num: 8, title: "Characterization Reports — BLA Submission Package", detail: "Process characterization reports are formal scientific documents filed in the BLA (Module 3.2.S.2.2). Each report covers a single unit operation: risk assessment, SDM qualification, DoE design and execution, statistical analysis, CPP classification with justification, NOR/PAR definition, and control strategy elements. Reports undergo multi-functional review (CMC, Regulatory, QA, Biostatistics) and are finalized to BLA-ready quality 6–12 months before planned submission." },
    ],
    duration: "18–30 months; typically spans late Phase 2 through Phase 3 start",
    team: "Process Sciences/CMC Development, Biostatistics, Analytical Development, CMC Regulatory",
    deliverables: [
      "Risk assessment report for each unit operation",
      "SDM qualification reports confirming commercial-scale representativeness",
      "DoE execution reports with full data packages",
      "CPP classification reports with statistical justification",
      "NOR/PAR and design space definitions",
      "Process control strategy document",
      "BLA-ready process characterization reports (Module 3.2.S.2.2)",
    ],
  },

  s12: {
    what: `Process Validation (PV) is the formal, regulatory-required demonstration that the commercial manufacturing process consistently produces drug substance and drug product meeting all predetermined specifications and quality attributes. FDA's 2011 Process Validation Guidance defines a three-stage lifecycle approach: Stage 1 (Process Design) encompasses all development and characterization work; Stage 2 (Process Performance Qualification, PPQ) is the formal validation campaign at commercial scale; Stage 3 (Continued Process Verification, CPV) is perpetual ongoing commercial monitoring.\n\nThe PPQ campaign — typically 3 consecutive commercial-scale batches, though statistically justified by other numbers — is the most critical manufacturing event in the pre-approval timeline. The PPQ batches are manufactured with rigorous enhanced sampling (more in-process samples than routine), tighter testing, and heightened documentation scrutiny. The PPQ protocol (what will be measured, how many samples, what acceptance criteria) must be approved by QA before execution begins.\n\nPPQ batches often contribute to the Phase 3 clinical supply, making this both a regulatory and a patient supply milestone. Failed PPQ batches can delay BLA filing by 12–24 months. Process Validation is never 'done' — Stage 3 CPV continues throughout the product's commercial lifetime with statistical monitoring of batch-to-batch consistency.`,
    before: `Receives from Stage 11: Completed process characterization package with CPP classification, design space, and control strategy. Receives from Stage 10: Commercial-scale manufacturing experience from Phase 3 clinical batches (which provide the pre-PPQ process performance database). Receives from regulatory affairs: PPQ protocol regulatory alignment (Pre-BLA meeting outcomes on statistical approach, batch number justification).`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 13 (Commercial Manufacturing): Validated commercial process with documented PPQ batches, approved commercial batch records, and an established Stage 3 CPV program. Delivers to Stage 15 (BLA): Process validation summary for Module 3.2.S.2.5. PPQ batches themselves often become the first commercial batches shipped post-approval.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Process Validation Master Plan (PVMP)", detail: "The PVMP is the overarching strategy document describing the approach, scope, organization, and timeline for all validation activities supporting BLA filing. It lists every unit operation, facility, analytical method, equipment system, utility, and computer system requiring validation/qualification. The PVMP also describes risk criteria for determining validation levels. FDA inspectors review the PVMP during PAI. A well-organized, current PVMP demonstrates that the organization has a systematic validation strategy rather than ad hoc validation activities." },
      { num: 2, title: "PPQ Protocol Development & Approval", detail: "The PPQ protocol is the pre-approved document that defines: scope (which batches, which unit operations, which manufacturing sites), sampling plan (enhanced in-process samples vs. routine monitoring — typically 3× the routine frequency), acceptance criteria (for each in-process attribute and end-point CQA, with statistical rationale), batch number justification (3-batch approach with confidence interval discussion, or alternative justification), personnel requirements (trained operators specifically assigned), and deviations handling plan. The protocol must be approved by QA and technically reviewed by CMC and Regulatory before execution begins." },
      { num: 3, title: "Stage 1 Evidence Compilation", detail: "Before PPQ execution, Stage 1 (Process Design) evidence is compiled and reviewed: all process development reports, SDM qualification data, process characterization reports, CPP classification, control strategy, analytical method validation reports, equipment qualification records, cleaning validation data (interim), and Phase 3 clinical manufacturing batch data. This review confirms that sufficient process understanding exists to justify proceeding to commercial-scale validation without foreseeable risk of PPQ failure." },
      { num: 4, title: "PPQ Batch Execution — Enhanced Sampling", detail: "PPQ batches are manufactured at commercial scale (or justified scale) using fully qualified equipment, cGMP raw materials, and trained, certified operators. Enhanced sampling is applied at every step: bioreactor — additional time points for VCD, metabolites, and in-process CQAs; harvest — additional turbidity and DNA samples; each chromatography step — additional column performance samples (conductivity, UV baseline, intermediate fractions for yield reconciliation); UF/DF — additional concentration and buffer exchange samples; DP filling — additional fill weight samples across the run. Enhanced documentation captures all process events." },
      { num: 5, title: "Cleaning Validation", detail: "Commercial-scale cleaning validation demonstrates that manufacturing equipment (bioreactors, chromatography columns, UF/DF systems, filling lines) can be cleaned to prevent cross-contamination and microbial growth between batches. The MACO (Maximum Allowable Carryover) is calculated using health-based exposure limits (PDE/ADE per ISPE/EMA guidance). Cleaning validation involves: worst-case soil (highest-concentration product contact surface), worst-case equipment (most difficult to clean), analytical verification (swab and rinse samples analyzed for protein residue using TOC or specific protein ELISA, plus visual inspection)." },
      { num: 6, title: "PPQ Data Analysis & Acceptance Criteria Assessment", detail: "After all PPQ batches are complete, the full data set is statistically analyzed against the pre-approved acceptance criteria: all release test results, enhanced in-process data, process performance statistics (mean, standard deviation, Cpk/Ppk for each critical parameter and attribute), and inter-batch comparability assessment. All acceptance criteria must be met for all three PPQ batches. Any PPQ batch that fails an acceptance criterion triggers an investigation — depending on root cause, the batch may be accepted with justification or the PPQ may require additional batches." },
      { num: 7, title: "Process Validation Report", detail: "The process validation report is the formal document summarizing the Stage 2 PPQ conclusions. Content: scope, protocol reference, batch numbers and dates, enhanced sampling data, acceptance criteria results, statistical analysis (Cpk/Ppk for all critical parameters), any deviations and their impact assessment, and validation conclusion statement. This report is a required BLA submission document (Module 3.2.S.2.5). It must be finalized, reviewed, and approved by QA before the BLA is submitted — incomplete validation reports are a common reason for BLA filing delays." },
      { num: 8, title: "Stage 3 CPV Program Launch", detail: "Concurrent with PPQ conclusion, the Stage 3 Continued Process Verification (CPV) program is formally established for commercial operations. CPV elements: control charts for all critical in-process parameters and release attributes (using Western Electric rules for out-of-control signals), Cpk/Ppk trending with alert (Cpk <1.33) and action (Cpk <1.0) thresholds, annual batch performance summary (feeding into APQR), and trend investigation procedures. CPV data is reviewed by Manufacturing Sciences and QA monthly and annually. FDA expects to see active CPV programs during Post-Approval Inspections." },
    ],
    duration: "PPQ execution: 3–6 months; full PV package completion: 6–12 months before BLA filing",
    team: "Manufacturing Sciences, GMP Manufacturing, QA Validation, QC, Regulatory Affairs, Biostatistics",
    deliverables: [
      "Process Validation Master Plan (PVMP)",
      "PPQ Protocol (approved pre-execution)",
      "PPQ Batch Records with enhanced sampling data",
      "Cleaning Validation report with MACO calculations",
      "Process Validation Report (Module 3.2.S.2.5)",
      "Stage 3 CPV Program documentation (control chart baseline, Cpk/Ppk baseline)",
    ],
  },

  s13: {
    what: `Commercial Manufacturing is the approved, validated, routine production of the drug for patients around the world. Once FDA (or EMA) approves the Biologics License Application (BLA), the drug can be commercially sold, and every batch manufactured must meet the approved specifications filed in the BLA. Commercial manufacturing is not development anymore — it is a regulated, validated, quality-system-controlled operation where deviation from the approved process requires formal documentation and potentially regulatory reporting.\n\nAt commercial scale, the manufacturing process runs continuously. A single commercial mAb program may require 30–100 production bioreactor runs per year to supply global demand. The manufacturing organization operates under an ISO 9001-like quality management system underpinned by cGMP regulations: every batch has a complete batch record, every deviation is investigated and closed, every raw material is qualified and released, every instrument is calibrated, every operator is trained, and every quality event is assessed for patient risk.\n\nContinued Process Verification (Stage 3) runs in parallel — statisticians and manufacturing scientists review real-time batch data against control charts, monitoring for parameter drift, CQA trends, or unexpected variation. Commercial manufacturing is where all the work of Stages 1–12 delivers its intended output: safe, effective drug for patients.`,
    before: `Receives from Stage 12: Validated commercial process, approved batch records, and commercial manufacturing site with qualified equipment and trained personnel. Receives from Stage 04: Commercial WCBs at manufacturing site. Receives regulatory approval from Stage 15 (BLA approval) authorizing commercial sale.`,
    after: `Delivers commercial drug product to the supply chain, wholesalers, and ultimately patients. Batch data feeds back to Stage 3 CPV (Stage 12). Post-approval manufacturing changes feed to Stage 16 (Post-Approval Lifecycle). Stability samples continue through Stage 14 (Stability). All batch records and QC data provide the basis for the Annual Product Quality Review (APQR).`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Annual Production Planning & Demand Forecasting", detail: "Commercial supply planning begins 12–18 months in advance with demand forecasting from sales, marketing, and clinical operations. A production schedule is developed listing: number of production campaigns, WCB lot assignments, raw material procurement quantities and lead times (long-lead items include custom bioprocessing media, viral filters, Protein A resin), manufacturing slot allocation, fill-finish scheduling, and QC testing capacity. Supply shortfalls or overproduction both have significant business consequences — commercial manufacturing organizations invest heavily in supply chain modeling." },
      { num: 2, title: "Raw Material Management & Release", detail: "Commercial manufacturing uses approved, qualified raw material suppliers and specifications filed in the BLA. For each manufacturing campaign: raw materials (bioreactor media, feeds, buffers, filter assemblies, single-use bioprocessing bags, chromatography resins, formulation excipients, primary packaging components) are ordered with sufficient lead time, received with complete documentation (supplier CoA, receiving inspection), tested against approved specifications by QC, and formally released before use. Critical Raw Materials (CRMs) — those with direct impact on CQAs — receive enhanced incoming testing." },
      { num: 3, title: "Routine Batch Manufacturing", detail: "Commercial batches follow the approved batch records exactly. The seed train begins with WCB vial thaw; cells expand through the seed train to production bioreactor inoculation; the fed-batch culture runs 12–18 days with daily IPC monitoring; harvest, clarification, and downstream purification follow in sequence. Commercial runs differ from Phase 3 clinical runs only in that enhanced PPQ sampling is no longer required — routine IPC sampling applies. All deviations (parameters outside action limits, equipment alarms, procedure deviations) are documented in deviation reports and investigated before batch disposition." },
      { num: 4, title: "In-Process and Release QC Testing", detail: "Commercial QC testing follows the approved specifications. In-process controls (bioreactor VCD, glucose, pH, DO daily; chromatography pH, conductivity, UV per step) are measured and compared against NORs and action limits. DS release testing: appearance, protein concentration, potency (vs. reference standard), purity (SEC-HPLC, CE-SDS), charge variants (icIEF), glycan profile (UHPLC), identity (peptide map), HCP (ELISA), residual DNA, Protein A leachate, endotoxin, bioburden. DP release testing adds: sterility, sub-visible particles (USP <787>), fill volume, container integrity, visual inspection (100% automated or manual)." },
      { num: 5, title: "Deviation Management & CAPA", detail: "Any departure from approved procedures, batch record steps, or specifications is documented in a deviation report. Deviations are assessed by QA for product impact: does this deviation affect patient safety, product efficacy, or product quality? Critical deviations (product safety impact) trigger immediate QA escalation and potential regulatory notification (21 CFR 312.32). All deviations are closed with root cause analysis and — if recurrent — a Corrective and Preventive Action (CAPA). The CAPA system tracks open actions, target dates, and effectiveness verification." },
      { num: 6, title: "Batch Disposition & QP Release", detail: "After all QC tests pass and all batch record deviations are closed, the QA team performs batch disposition review. The completed batch record is reviewed for cGMP compliance: all steps performed, all IPCs within limits (or deviations justified), all raw material release records present, all equipment calibration current, all personnel training current. The QP (EU)/QA Director (US) signs the batch disposition record and Certificate of Analysis, formally releasing the lot. Released lots are assigned to specific distribution destinations with associated temperatures and shipping qualification data." },
      { num: 7, title: "Continued Process Verification (Stage 3 CPV)", detail: "Every commercial batch contributes data to the Stage 3 CPV program. Key process parameters and CQAs are plotted on Shewhart control charts. Statistical alerts (Western Electric rules: one point beyond 3σ; two of three beyond 2σ; trends of 7 consecutive points in one direction) are investigated. Monthly and annual CPV reports summarize Cpk/Ppk values for all critical attributes, highlighting any negative trends. FDA expects manufacturing scientists to proactively investigate and resolve CPV signals before they escalate to specification failures." },
      { num: 8, title: "Annual Product Quality Review (APQR)", detail: "ICH Q10 and 21 CFR 211.180(e) require an Annual Product Quality Review (APQR) for each product. The APQR compiles: all batch records, QC results, OOS/OOT events, deviations and CAPAs, change controls, stability data updates, CPV trends, and supply chain quality events for the calendar year. The APQR conclusions assess whether the product is in a state of control, identifies adverse trends, and proposes improvement actions. APQRs are reviewed by the site Head of Quality and shared with the product's regulatory teams." },
    ],
    duration: "Perpetual — commercial manufacturing continues throughout the product's lifecycle (typically 15–30+ years)",
    team: "GMP Manufacturing Operators, Manufacturing Sciences, QC, QA, Quality Systems, Supply Chain, Regulatory CMC (post-approval changes)",
    deliverables: [
      "Completed batch records for all commercial lots",
      "Certificates of Analysis (CoA) for each released lot",
      "Monthly/Annual CPV reports",
      "Annual Product Quality Review (APQR)",
      "Deviation investigation reports and CAPA records",
    ],
  },

  s14: {
    what: `Stability and Shelf Life studies generate the data that determines how long the drug product can be stored and remains safe and effective. The shelf life printed on the drug product label (e.g., 'Use by December 2027, Store at 2–8°C') is supported by real-time stability data showing the drug meets all its specifications until that date. Without adequate stability data, no drug can receive regulatory approval.\n\nThe regulatory framework is ICH Q5C (stability testing for biotechnological products), which defines the required storage conditions, time points, and attributes to be tested. ICH Q1A(R2) provides supplementary guidance on accelerated and intermediate testing. Studies are placed under multiple temperature conditions: long-term (5°C refrigerated), accelerated (25°C/60%RH — to stress the molecule and generate data faster), and potentially intermediate (30°C/65%RH) and frozen (−20°C or −70°C for some formulations).\n\nStability studies are time-dependent and irreversible — a missed time point cannot be recovered. Programs must initiate stability studies at every defined stage: development lots, Phase 1 clinical lots, Phase 3 PPQ lots, and commercial lots. The shelf life can only be proposed based on available real-time data at the time of BLA filing, then extended by supplemental stability data post-approval.`,
    before: `Receives samples from every development and manufacturing stage: development drug substance lots (for early formulation screening), Phase 1 and Phase 3 clinical drug product lots (for regulatory commitments), PPQ lots (for commercial shelf life establishment), and every commercial lot (for ongoing stability commitments). Also receives from Stage 07: stability-indicating analytical methods.`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 15 (BLA): Real-time stability data supporting the proposed shelf life and storage conditions for inclusion in the BLA. Delivers to Stage 13 (Commercial Manufacturing): Shelf-life limits that define distribution conditions and expiry. Post-approval, delivers to Stage 16: Stability data supporting label updates and shelf-life extensions.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Stability-Indicating Method Identification & Forced Degradation", detail: "Before formal stability studies begin, forced degradation studies identify which analytical methods detect each relevant degradation pathway: thermal stress (2 weeks at 40°C) detects aggregation-prone conditions; oxidative stress (H₂O₂ + metal catalysts) challenges Met/Trp oxidation; acid/base stress (pH 3.0/pH 10.0, 24h) reveals deamidation and fragmentation; UV photostress (ICH Q1B) evaluates photodegradation. Methods that show changes in stressed samples but not in unstressed controls are confirmed as stability-indicating. These methods form the core stability test panel." },
      { num: 2, title: "ICH Zone Determination & Storage Condition Selection", detail: "The ICH climate zone determines the required stability storage conditions based on the intended global distribution markets. Zone I/II (US, Europe, Japan): long-term 25°C/60%RH + accelerated 40°C/75%RH. Zone III/IV (developing world markets): long-term 30°C/65%RH or 40°C/75%RH. Biological products are typically stored refrigerated (5°C ± 3°C) — their stability test conditions include: 5°C (long-term, primary condition), 25°C/60%RH (accelerated condition for refrigerated products — rarely used for biologics as instability is rapid), and −20°C or −70°C (for frozen drug substance)." },
      { num: 3, title: "Stability Protocol Design", detail: "The stability protocol defines: product lots to be placed (with batch numbers, concentrations, fill volumes, container-closure system), storage conditions and chamber specifications, time points (ICH Q5C guidance: 0, 3, 6, 9, 12, 18, 24 months for long-term; 0, 1, 3, 6 months for accelerated), test panel at each time point (not all tests at every time point — a tiered approach reduces resource burden while ensuring stability-indicating tests are complete), acceptance criteria (same as release specifications for most attributes), and sample number (at least 3 samples per time point for statistical calculations)." },
      { num: 4, title: "Sample Placement & Initial Time Point Testing", detail: "Stability samples are placed into qualified stability chambers (temperature ± 2°C and RH ± 5% tolerance, continuous chart recorder monitoring) immediately upon manufacturing. The initial time point (T=0) is tested within 30 days of manufacture and serves as the baseline. Each stability sample is accompanied by a stability study card showing the product, lot number, storage condition, pull schedule, and test plan. Chain-of-custody is maintained throughout — samples pulled on the exact scheduled time point (±7 days for monthly points, ±14 days for 12+ month points per ICH guidance)." },
      { num: 5, title: "Real-Time and Accelerated Testing Execution", detail: "At each scheduled time point, samples are pulled from stability chambers and tested against the stability panel. Key attributes tracked over time: aggregation (SEC-HPLC %HMWS — typically increases over time), potency (cell-based %RA — must remain within 80–125% or 70–130%), charge variants (icIEF acidic peak % — deamidation causes acidic shift over time), oxidation (peptide map Met/Trp oxidized peptide %RA), sub-visible particles (MFI count at 1–100 µm), protein concentration, and appearance. Any trend approaching a specification limit triggers a stability alert and proactive formulation review." },
      { num: 6, title: "Shelf Life Determination — Statistical Methods", detail: "The shelf life is statistically determined as the time point at which the 95% one-sided confidence bound of the degradation trend (typically linear regression of the attribute vs. time) intersects the specification limit. This is the T90 calculation for potency or the aggregation trend intersection. FDA recommends fitting linear regression to each stability attribute and using the confidence interval approach. The proposed shelf life is the minimum time across all attributes. For a product with complex degradation kinetics, Arrhenius-based accelerated stability modeling may be used to predict long-term behavior from accelerated conditions." },
      { num: 7, title: "Photostability Testing (ICH Q1B)", detail: "ICH Q1B requires exposure of the drug product (in the proposed container-closure and secondary packaging) to cool white fluorescent light (≥1.2 million lux-hours) and near UV (≥200 W·h/m²). Results determine: whether the drug is photolabile and requires light-protective primary packaging (amber vials, opaque secondary packaging); the maximum light exposure time during patient handling; and whether any photo-degradation products are potential safety concerns. Photostability data is included in the BLA Module 3 stability section." },
      { num: 8, title: "BLA Stability Data Package & Ongoing Commitment", detail: "The BLA stability submission includes: stability protocols, all data from Phase 1 and Phase 3 clinical lot studies, PPQ lot stability data (≥6 months real-time at the time of submission), a statistical analysis of degradation trends, the proposed shelf life and storage conditions justification. FDA typically requires 6 months minimum real-time data at the proposed storage condition before approving a shelf life of 24 months. Post-approval, stability commitments continue: commercial lots placed annually into the ongoing stability program; any out-of-trend result investigated and potentially reported as a Field Alert Report (FAR) or BLA supplement." },
    ],
    duration: "Continuous from first development lots through commercial lifecycle; real-time studies run for the full proposed shelf life (typically 18–36 months)",
    team: "Stability Sciences, QC Analytical, Formulation Development, CMC Regulatory",
    deliverables: [
      "Forced degradation study report with stability-indicating method confirmation",
      "Stability protocols for all study types (long-term, accelerated, photostability)",
      "Stability data reports at each time point for clinical and PPQ lots",
      "Shelf life proposal with statistical analysis (T90, regression, confidence intervals)",
      "BLA stability data package (Module 3.2.P.8)",
      "Ongoing stability commitment records for commercial manufacturing",
    ],
  },

  s15: {
    what: `BLA Filing is the culmination of 5–10 years of development work — the compilation of all CMC, clinical, nonclinical, and pharmacology data into a single regulatory submission asking FDA (or EMA for a Marketing Authorization Application, MAA) to approve the drug for commercial sale. For CMC, this means assembling Module 3 of the Common Technical Document (CTD) — typically 10,000–50,000 pages of process descriptions, analytical method validations, specifications, stability data, container-closure studies, and manufacturing information in the highly structured eCTD format.\n\nThe BLA is not just a document assembly project. Every claim made in the BLA (this CPP range ensures CQA quality; this specification is clinically justified; this shelf life is supported by real-time data) must be backed by data already in hand. Gaps discovered during BLA preparation require either gap-filling studies (which take time) or a revised submission strategy. The Pre-BLA meeting with FDA (Type B meeting, typically 12–18 months before planned submission) is the opportunity to align on CMC expectations, confirm analytical package sufficiency, and identify any potential deficiencies before they become Complete Response Letters (CRLs).\n\nFDA has 12 months standard review or 6 months priority review (for breakthrough therapies or serious conditions with unmet need) to complete their review. During this time, FDA reviewers scrutinize every aspect of the CMC package. A Pre-Approval Inspection (PAI) of the manufacturing site is conducted by FDA investigators, who verify that submitted data accurately reflects manufacturing practice and that the site is cGMP-compliant.`,
    before: `Receives from all previous stages: Process characterization data (Stage 11), Process validation reports (Stage 12), Stability data (Stage 14), Analytical validation reports (Stage 07), Formulation development reports (Stage 08), Cell bank testing data (Stage 04), and manufacturing history from Stages 10/13. Also receives clinical data (Module 5), nonclinical data (Module 4), and pharmacology data (Module 2) from other functional areas.`,
    after: `Delivers to Stage 16 (Post-Approval Lifecycle): An approved BLA defining all 'Established Conditions' (ECs per ICH Q12) — the specific process parameters, material specifications, and manufacturing controls that are locked by the approval. All subsequent manufacturing changes must be evaluated against the approved BLA. Also initiates commercial supply (Stage 13) and post-marketing commitments.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Module 3 Architecture Planning", detail: "The CMC team, led by CMC Regulatory, plans the BLA Module 3 architecture: 3.2.S (Drug Substance — sections S.1 through S.7 covering manufacturer, structure, development, manufacturing, characterization, specifications, and stability) and 3.2.P (Drug Product — P.1 through P.8 covering description, composition, pharmaceutical development, manufacturing, characterization, specifications, and stability), plus supporting drug substance and drug product appendices. A content matrix is developed mapping every required section to the responsible author, data owner, and availability timeline. This matrix drives the BLA preparation Gantt chart." },
      { num: 2, title: "Quality Overall Summary (QOS) Writing", detail: "The QOS (Module 2.3) is a concise reviewer-friendly narrative (typically 50–150 pages) that summarizes the entire Module 3 content. FDA and EMA reviewers read the QOS first — it sets the tone for the entire review. The QOS explains: what the molecule is, how it's made, how quality is controlled, and why specifications are appropriate. Effective QOS writing tells a coherent quality story rather than simply summarizing data tables. The QOS is written last (after all Module 3 sections are stable) but is the most strategically important CMC document." },
      { num: 3, title: "Pre-BLA Meeting with FDA (Type B)", detail: "12–18 months before planned submission, a Type B Pre-BLA meeting request is submitted to FDA with specific CMC questions: Is our specification setting approach adequate? Is our process validation package complete? Are there additional stability data points required? Is our container-closure extractables/leachables approach acceptable? FDA responses to these questions can prevent CRLs. The meeting request includes data summaries and proposed approaches for each question — specific questions with supporting data summaries get more useful responses than vague questions." },
      { num: 4, title: "eCTD Assembly & Quality Review", detail: "The BLA is assembled in eCTD (electronic Common Technical Document) format — a standardized electronic submission structure with hyperlinked content, granular bookmarks, and validation against FDA's technical specifications. Every Module 3 section must have hyperlinks to source data, cross-references to related sections, and all referenced methods, validation reports, and data summaries attached as appendices. QC review of the eCTD checks: completeness against the content matrix, cross-reference accuracy, data consistency between sections, and technical validation (no broken links, correct metadata)." },
      { num: 5, title: "BLA Submission", detail: "The BLA is submitted electronically via the FDA Electronic Submissions Gateway (ESG) as a single eCTD sequence. At submission, FDA issues a 60-day filing decision (whether the application is sufficiently complete to file for review) followed by formal acceptance or refuse-to-file (RTF). If accepted, FDA assigns a PDUFA review date (12 or 6 months from receipt date). The clock starts. For EMA MAAs, submission is to EMEA, triggering the 210-day Centralized Procedure with clock stops for questions." },
      { num: 6, title: "FDA Review — Information Requests & Deficiency Letters", detail: "During the review period, FDA reviewers generate Information Requests (IRs), Discipline Review Letters (DRLs), or a Complete Response Letter (CRL) if deficiencies are identified. CRLs are the most serious — they represent FDA's determination that the application is not approvable as submitted. CMC CRL triggers include: insufficient process validation data, specification not clinically justified, instability of proposed shelf life, inadequate viral clearance data, or cGMP deficiencies from PAI. Responses to IRs/CRLs must be thorough and rapid (typically 30–90 day response windows)." },
      { num: 7, title: "Pre-Approval Inspection (PAI)", detail: "FDA investigators conduct a PAI of the commercial manufacturing site(s) 3–12 months before the PDUFA date. PAI focuses on: data integrity (are submitted data consistent with source records?), process validation (do executed PPQ runs match submitted protocols and reports?), OOS investigations (were previous OOS events properly investigated?), cGMP compliance (are procedures followed, equipment qualified, personnel trained?). PAI findings can be 483 observations (non-critical) or Warning Letters (serious, may delay approval). PAI preparation begins 6–12 months before the expected inspection with comprehensive readiness activities." },
      { num: 8, title: "Approval & Product Launch", detail: "If FDA finds the application approvable with no outstanding CMC issues, FDA issues an Approval Letter on or before the PDUFA date. The approval includes the Prescribing Information (label), approved manufacturing conditions, post-marketing stability commitments (specific lots to be placed annually), and any post-approval commitments (PMRs — Post-Marketing Requirements; PMCs — Post-Marketing Commitments). Commercial distribution can begin immediately upon approval. The final approved label and specifications are the permanent reference point for all future manufacturing and post-approval changes." },
    ],
    duration: "BLA preparation: 12–24 months; FDA review: 10–12 months standard, 6–8 months priority; total from filing to approval: 12–18 months",
    team: "CMC Regulatory Affairs, CMC Development leads, Quality Assurance, Clinical, Nonclinical, Regulatory Program Management",
    deliverables: [
      "Completed BLA/MAA eCTD submission",
      "Quality Overall Summary (QOS, Module 2.3)",
      "Module 3 complete: all S and P sections with supporting data",
      "Pre-BLA meeting minutes with FDA commitments",
      "Response to FDA Information Requests",
      "Approved BLA with Prescribing Information and label",
    ],
  },

  s16: {
    what: `Post-Approval and Lifecycle Management encompasses everything that happens to the CMC program after the initial BLA approval — and it typically spans decades. The commercial product does not stand still. Manufacturing processes are improved (for cost, sustainability, or quality), raw material suppliers change, equipment is upgraded, manufacturing sites are added or retired, and analytical methods are enhanced. Every one of these changes must be evaluated against the approved BLA, risk-assessed, and — depending on risk level — either reported to FDA or approved by FDA before implementation.\n\nICH Q12 (2019) provides the modern framework for lifecycle management: the concept of Established Conditions (ECs) defines exactly which elements of the BLA require regulatory notification when changed. Well-designed ECs maximize manufacturing flexibility while ensuring patient safety. Post-Approval Change Management Protocols (PACMPs) allow pre-negotiating the regulatory pathway for anticipated future changes — converting a Prior Approval Supplement (12-month FDA review) to a Changes Being Effected (30-day wait period).\n\nFrom the commercial competitive standpoint, lifecycle management includes product line extensions (new indications, new presentations, pediatric formulations, subcutaneous versions), defense against biosimilar competition (through continued process improvement, second-generation devices, and line extensions that refresh the commercial profile), and eventual product discontinuation with proper regulatory notification and knowledge archiving.`,
    before: `Receives from Stage 15: The approved BLA with all Established Conditions locked. Receives from Stage 13: Ongoing commercial manufacturing data, CPV trends, and batch quality events that may identify need for process improvements. Receives from clinical teams: New indication data, post-marketing surveillance, safety signals that may require label changes.`,
    after: `Perpetual lifecycle activity. Feeds back to Stage 13 (Commercial Manufacturing) with approved process changes. May initiate new development work in Stages 05–12 for major process changes requiring full characterization and validation. Provides the basis for biosimilar reference product characterization packages used by competitors.`,
    steps: [
      { num: 1, title: "Post-Approval Change Classification & Filing Strategy", detail: "Every manufacturing change — raw material supplier, process parameter, analytical method, specification, container-closure, manufacturing site, batch size — must be evaluated against the approved BLA and classified by regulatory impact. FDA's post-approval guidance and ICH Q12 define three categories: Prior Approval Supplement (PAS — highest impact, requires FDA approval before implementation, typically 12-month review); Changes Being Effected in 30 Days (CBE-30 — moderate impact, FDA has 30 days to object before implementation); Annual Report (lowest impact, reported in annual batch record compilation). Incorrect classification (e.g., filing a PAS change as Annual Report) is a regulatory violation." },
      { num: 2, title: "Comparability Studies (ICH Q5E)", detail: "When a manufacturing change is made — a new raw material, a process parameter shift, a different bioreactor, or a new purification column — ICH Q5E requires demonstrating that the post-change product is comparable to the pre-change product for all clinically relevant CQAs. The comparability exercise has three tiers: analytical comparability (full side-by-side characterization of pre- and post-change material); functional/biological comparability (potency and relevant in vitro studies); and, if analytical and functional comparability is not sufficient, clinical comparability (PK/PD bridging study). Most post-approval changes are managed at the analytical level only." },
      { num: 3, title: "Post-Approval Change Management Protocols (PACMPs)", detail: "ICH Q12 PACMPs allow sponsors to pre-agree with FDA on the regulatory pathway for future anticipated changes. Example: a sponsor files a PACMP describing exactly how they would evaluate a future manufacturing site change (comparability protocol, analytical methods, acceptance criteria, validation requirements). FDA approves the PACMP upfront. When the actual change is made, if it conforms to the PACMP, it can be filed as CBE-30 instead of PAS — saving 12+ months of regulatory review time. PACMPs are particularly valuable for predictable changes like new bioreactor installation, vendor qualification, or site redundancy." },
      { num: 4, title: "Continued Process Verification (CPV) & APQR", detail: "The Stage 3 CPV program (established at Stage 12) continues perpetually for all commercial lots. Annual Product Quality Reviews compile: all batch data, OOS/OOT events, deviations, change controls, stability updates, CPV trends, and customer complaints for the year. The APQR formally assesses whether the product remains in a state of control and identifies improvement opportunities. Adverse trends in CPV (e.g., steady drift in glycan profile over 3 years without specification failure) are flagged for proactive investigation before they become batch failures — proactive management is far less costly than reactive batch failures." },
      { num: 5, title: "Lifecycle Formulation Improvements — SC, Auto-Injector", detail: "A major commercial lifecycle investment is developing new product presentations: transitioning from IV infusion to subcutaneous auto-injector (requires high-concentration formulation development, viscosity reduction, device HFE studies, extractables/leachables from device-drug contact, and bioavailability bridging); transitioning from lyophilized to liquid formulation (stability improvement, patient convenience); developing pediatric formulations (dose range, palatability, smaller fill volumes). Each new presentation is filed as a BLA supplement and requires its own clinical and CMC development program, including comparability to the approved formulation." },
      { num: 6, title: "Biosimilar Reference Product Strategy", detail: "Once the originator's reference product is approved, biosimilar manufacturers begin extensive characterization of the reference product. The originator's post-approval manufacturing changes affect the biosimilar similarity target — if the reference product's glycan profile shifts due to a process change, biosimilars filed against the original profile must reassess their similarity. Originator CMC teams must understand how their own post-approval changes affect the biosimilar landscape, and should ensure that process changes are well-documented and filed appropriately (not made as undisclosed process variations that could complicate the reference product characterization picture)." },
      { num: 7, title: "Post-Marketing Stability — Label Updates & Extensions", detail: "Post-approval, ongoing stability studies may support shelf-life extensions beyond the initially approved shelf life. When sufficient additional real-time data is accumulated (e.g., 36 months of data now supports a 36-month instead of 24-month shelf life), a CBE-30 supplement updates the label. Conversely, if stability data shows degradation approaching specification limits earlier than expected, the shelf life must be shortened via a PAS. Post-marketing surveillance for stability-related adverse events (visible particles, potency failures) may also trigger stability protocol modifications." },
      { num: 8, title: "Product Discontinuation & CMC Knowledge Archiving", detail: "When commercial product is discontinued, FDA must be notified 6 months in advance (21 CFR 314.81). All batch records, QC data, stability records, validation reports, and regulatory correspondence must be retained for the product lifetime plus a defined period (21 CFR 211.180 — typically the greater of 3 years post-manufacture or product lifetime + 1 year). CMC knowledge archiving — the full technical understanding of the product and process — is a corporate asset enabling future product restoration, technology transfer to a new partner, or data mining for platform programs. ALCOA+ documentation principles ensure the integrity of all archived records." },
    ],
    duration: "Perpetual — the lifecycle management program continues for the entire commercial life of the product",
    team: "CMC Regulatory Affairs, Manufacturing Sciences, QA, Commercial Operations, Device Engineering (combination products), Biosimilar Intelligence Team",
    deliverables: [
      "Post-approval change management records (PAS/CBE-30/Annual Report filings)",
      "Comparability reports (ICH Q5E) for each manufacturing change",
      "PACMP filings for anticipated future changes",
      "Annual Product Quality Reviews (APQRs)",
      "Lifecycle formulation/device development packages",
      "Ongoing CPV monitoring reports",
    ],
  },

};
